ke Mills]]\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories]]''\n| Victoria (voice)\n| [[Noah Baumbach]]\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]''\n| Tracy Walker (voice)\n| [[Wes Anderson]] \n|\n|-\n|} \n<!--DO NOT USE ROWSPANS PER WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n<!-- Per WP:NFF and WP:CRYSTAL, do not add films that are listed as \"pre-production\" -->\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2011\u201315\n| ''[[China, IL]]''\n| Pony Merks (voice)\n| 21 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''The Corrections''\n| Julia Vrais\n| Unaired [[HBO]] pilot\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''How I Met Your Dad''\n| Sally\n| Unaired [[CBS]] pilot\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Portlandia (TV series)|Portlandia]]''\n| Mermaid\n| Episode: \"Doug Becomes a Feminist\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Mindy Project]]''\n| Sarah Branum\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Ms. Reynolds\n| Uncredited; Episode: \"[[Saoirse Ronan]]/[[U2]]\"\n|}\n\n== Theatre ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Venue\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2014 || ''[[The Village Bike]]'' || Becky || [[MCC Theater]], Off-Broadway || rowspan=2|<ref>https://www.broadwayworld.com/people/Greta-Gerwig/</ref>\n|-\n|2020 || ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' || Performer || [[New York Theatre Workshop]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Greta Gerwig}}\n\nIn 2011, Gerwig won an award from the [[Athena Film Festival]] for her artistry as one of [[Hollywood]]'s definitive screen actresses of her generation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://athenafilmfestival.com/awards/award-winners/2011-athena-award-winners/ |title=2011 Athena Award Winners |publisher=[[Athena Film Festival]] |accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, she was selected as a member of the jury for the [[64th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/01/james-schamus-will-head-berlin-jury-that-includes-christoph-waltz-greta-gerwig-and-michel-gondry-31370/ |title=James Schamus Will Head Berlin Jury That Includes Christoph Waltz, Greta Gerwig and Michel Gondry |date=January 14, 2014 |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, her nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] at the [[90th Academy Awards]] for ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'' made her the first woman in eight years (and one of only five women in Oscar history) to have been nominated in that category.<ref name=\"Gonzalez\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/oscars-greta-gerwig-gets-first-female-director-nod-in-eight-years-11219567 |title=Oscars 2018: Greta Gerwig gets first female director nomination in eight years |date=January 23, 2018 |publisher=[[Sky News]] |accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Gerwig's work on ''Lady Bird'' was nominated for sixteen awards in notable circuits, winning six of those awards.<ref name=\"NBR\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/golden-globes-2018-lady-bird-wins-best-motion-picture-musical-or-comedy/ |title=Golden Globes 2018: Lady Bird Wins Best Motion Picture, Musical or Comedy |last=Wicks |first=Amanda |date=January 8, 2018 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=March 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/national-society-film-critics-winners-2018-list-full-1072167 |title='Lady Bird' Named Best Picture by National Society of Film Critics |last=Lewis |first=Hilary |date=January 6, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of female film and television directors]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister links|d=Q271967|c=Category:Greta Gerwig|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|q=no}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Greta Gerwig|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Greta Gerwig|Awards for Greta Gerwig]]\n| list =\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gerwig, Greta}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American Unitarian Universalists]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film director, screenwriter and actress}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Greta Gerwig\n| image        = Greta Gerwig Berlinale 2018.jpg\n| caption      = Gerwig at the [[68th Berlin International Film Festival|2018 Berlin International Film Festival]]\n| birth_name   = Greta Celeste Gerwig\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1983|8|4}}\n| birth_place  = [[Sacramento, California]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| alma_mater   = [[Barnard College]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actress|filmmaker}}\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n| partner      = [[Noah Baumbach]] (2011\u2013present)\n| children     = 1\n| awards       = [[List of awards and nominations received by Greta Gerwig|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Greta Celeste Gerwig''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|g|\u025c\u02d0r|w|\u026a|g}};<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QJE_r2UrYLo |title=Noah Baumbach & Greta Gerwig \u2013 Personal Palace Cinemas Introduction |date=August 13, 2015 |publisher=[[Palace Cinemas (Central Europe)|Palace Cinemas]] |accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref> born August 4, 1983) is an American actress and filmmaker.<!--Do not reverse the order--> She first garnered attention after working on and appearing in several [[Mumblecore|mumblecore films]].<ref name=\"Bunbury\">{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/real-to-reel-the-rise-of-mumblecore-20130719-2q8rr.html |title=Real to reel: The rise of 'mumblecore' |last=Bunbury |first=Stephanie |date=July 19, 2013 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sweetheart\">{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/movies/features/64475/ |title=Sweetheart of Early-Adult Angst |last=Larocca |first=Amy |date=March 7, 2010 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> Between 2006 and 2009, she appeared in a number of films by [[Joe Swanberg]], some of which she co-wrote or co-directed, including ''[[Hannah Takes the Stairs]]'' (2007) and ''[[Nights and Weekends]]'' (2008).<ref name=\"Georgia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.straight.com/movies/393071/mumblecore-queen-greta-gerwig-laughs-last-frances-ha |title=Mumblecore queen Greta Gerwig laughs last in Frances Ha |last=Eisner |first=Ken |date=June 20, 2013 |work=[[The Georgia Straight]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince the early 2010s, Gerwig has collaborated with her partner [[Noah Baumbach]] on several films, including ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]'' (2010), ''[[Frances Ha]]'' (2012), for which she received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination, and ''[[Mistress America]]'' (2015). She has also appeared in [[Whit Stillman]]'s  ''[[Damsels in Distress (film)|Damsels in Distress]]'' (2011), [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[To Rome with Love (film)|To Rome with Love]]'' (2012), [[Rebecca Miller]]'s ''[[Maggie's Plan]]'' (2015), [[Pablo Larra\u00edn]]'s ''[[Jackie (2016 film)|Jackie]]'' (2016), and [[Mike Mills (director)|Mike Mills]]' ''[[20th Century Women]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/12/20th-century-women-best-actress-mike-mills-annette-bening-greta-gerwig-1201761301/ |title='20th Century Women': How Mike Mills Empowered Annette Bening and Greta Gerwig |last=Thompson |first=Anne |date=December 21, 2016 |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/la-la-land-grabs-massive-12-nominations-to-lead-all-movies-in-critics-choice-awards-1201862593/ |title='La La Land' Grabs Massive 12 Nominations To Lead All Movies In Critics' Choice Awards |last=Hammond |first=Pete |date=December 1, 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGerwig has had two solo directorial ventures, the coming-of-age films ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'' (2017) and ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]'' (2019), both of which earned nominations for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. For the former, she received [[Academy Award]] nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]],<ref name=\"Gonzalez\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/01/23/entertainment/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-oscar-nomination/index.html |title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' best director nomination is a huge deal |last=Gonzalez |first=Sandra |date=February 26, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> and for the latter, she was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]].\n\n==Early life==\nGerwig was born in [[Sacramento, California]] and grew up in the River Park neighborhood.<ref name=\"Hubler\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sacbee.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/shawn-hubler/article69510342.html |title=Will someone help Greta Gerwig make her ode to Sacramento? |last=Hubler |first=Shawn |date=April 2, 2016 |work=[[The Sacramento Bee]] |accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> She is the daughter of Christine (n\u00e9e Sauer), an [[Obstetrics and gynaecology|Ob-Gyn]] nurse, and Gordon Gerwig, who worked for a [[credit union]] on small business loans.<ref name=\"Hubler\"/><ref name=\"Smallwood\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/01/magazine/greta-gerwigs-radical-confidence.html |title=Greta Gerwig's Radical Confidence |last=Smallwood |first=Christine |date=November 1, 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=November 1, 2017 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She is close to her parents and they make an appearance in ''Frances Ha'' as her character's parents.<ref name=\"Smallwood\" /> She has an older brother, a landscape architect, and sister, a manager at the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/09/greta-gerwig-eden-the-humbling |title=Greta Gerwig Is Sorry Her Little Brother Didn't Get to Watch ''How I Met Your Dad'' |date=September 7, 2014 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Gilbey\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article7142687.ece |title=Greta Gerwig \u2013 great expectations |last=Gilbey |first=Ryan |date=June 6, 2010 |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |accessdate=June 6, 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/greta-gerwig-the-queen-of-lowbudget-cinema-is-breaking-into-the-mainstream-with-her-role-in-arthur-2267216.html |title=Greta Gerwig: The queen of low-budget cinema is breaking into the mainstream with her role in Arthur |last=Adams |first=Guy |date=April 16, 2011 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> Gerwig has German, Irish, and English ancestry.<ref name=\"Gilbey\"/>\n\nGerwig was raised a [[Unitarian Universalism|Unitarian Universalist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uuworld.org/ideas/articles/289465.shtml |title=Greta Gerwig, UU film star |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=August 15, 2013 |work=[[The Christian Register|UU World]] |accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> She attended [[St. Francis High School (Sacramento, California)|St. Francis High School]], an all-girls [[Catholic school]] in Sacramento, and graduated in 2002.<ref name=\"Smallwood\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stfrancishs.org/page/the-arts/alumnae-in-the-arts |title= St. Francis Catholic High School Alumnae in the Arts |access-date=February 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618075950/https://www.stfrancishs.org/page/the-arts/alumnae-in-the-arts |archive-date=June 18, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She has described herself as having been \"an intense child.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/the-reel-breakdown/rome-love-star-greta-gerwig-wild-woody-allen-214237354.html |title='To Rome With Love' star Greta Gerwig is wild about Woody Allen \u2014 just read her high school yearbook |last=Adams |first=Thelma |date=June 22, 2012 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Brockes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jul/13/greta-gerwig-frances-ha |title=Greta Gerwig: daydream believer |last=Brockes |first=Emma |date=July 13, 2013 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> Gerwig showed an early interest in dance and later took up competitive [[fencing]], but had to quit in part due to the high costs.<ref name=\"Brockes\" /><ref name =\"NPR2017\">{{cite news|url = https://www.npr.org/transcripts/564579012?storyId=564579012?storyId=564579012 |title = Greta Gerwig Explores Mother-Daughter Love (And Angst) In 'Lady Bird' |website = [[NPR]] |date = November 16, 2017 |accessdate = January 25, 2020|last = Gross |first = Terry}}</ref> She had intended to complete a degree in musical theatre in [[New York (state)|New York]], but ended up graduating from [[Barnard College]] with a degree in English and philosophy.<ref name=\"Brockes\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hannahtakesthestairs.com/cast.html |title=Hannah Takes The Stairs |accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> Outside class, she performed in the [[Columbia University]] [[Varsity Show]] with [[Kate McKinnon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/spring14/cover_story0 |title=Varsity Show Endears and Endures &#124; Columbia College Today |last=Vinciguerra |first=Thomas |date=Spring 2014 |publisher=[[Columbia University]] |accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132009: Early career===\nGerwig originally intended to become a [[playwright]], but turned to acting when she was not admitted to playwriting [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] programs.<ref name=\"Smallwood\" /> In 2006, while still studying at Barnard, she was cast in a minor role in [[Joe Swanberg]]'s ''[[LOL (2006 film)|LOL]]'', and appeared in ''[[Baghead]]'' by [[Jay Duplass|Jay]] and [[Mark Duplass]]. She began a partnership with Swanberg, which resulted in the duo's co-writing ''[[Hannah Takes the Stairs]]'' (2007), and sharing both writing and directing duties on ''[[Nights and Weekends]]'' (2008). Through these films, she became known as a key figure in the rising [[mumblecore]] film movement,<ref name=\"Bunbury\" /><ref name=\"Sweetheart\" /> often referred to as an \"[[it girl]]\".<ref name=\"Georgia\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2008/jul/26/entertainment/et-greta26 |title=The accidental 'It' girl |last=Olsen |first=Mark |date=July 26, 2008 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018 |issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/lola-versus-indie-it-girl-greta-gerwig-still-has-it/article4264889/ |title=Lola Versus: Indie It girl Greta Gerwig still has it |last=Punter |first=Jennie |date=June 15, 2012 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> Although she had an association with a number of other mumblecore filmmakers and appeared in several films, mainstream success remained elusive.\n\nOf this period in her life, Gerwig has said, \"I was really depressed. I was 25 [in 2008] and thinking, 'This is supposed to be the best time and I'm miserable' but it felt like acting was happening for me, and I went back to acting classes.\"<ref name=\"Brockes\" />\n\n===2010\u20132016: Mainstream success===\n[[File:Greta Gerwig, No Strings Attached Premiere (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Gerwig at the premiere of ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]'' in January 2011]]\n\nIn 2010, Gerwig starred in [[Noah Baumbach]]'s ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]'' with [[Ben Stiller]], [[Rhys Ifans]], and [[Jennifer Jason Leigh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/28/the-nifty-50-greta-gerwig-actress/ |title=The Nifty 50 {{!}} Greta Gerwig, Actress |last=Heyman |first=Stephen |date=January 28, 2010 |publisher=[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine|T Magazine]] |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.observer.com/2009/o2/noah-baumbach-hires-mumblecores-meryl-streep-readies-i-greenberg-i |title=Noah Baumbach Hires Mumblecore's Meryl Streep, Readies Greenberg |last=Rosen |first=Christopher |date=February 9, 2009 |work=[[The New York Observer]] |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> In an appraisal of her work in this and other films, ''[[The New York Times]]'' critic [[A. O. Scott]] described Gerwig as an \"ambassador of a cinematic style that often seems opposed to the very idea of style.\" \"She seems to be embarked on a project,\" Scott wrote, \"however piecemeal and modestly scaled, of redefining just what it is we talk about when we talk about acting.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/28/movies/28scott.html |title=No Method To Her Method |last=Scott |first=A. O. |date=March 24, 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> In 2010, Gerwig made her first talk show appearance on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. From 2011 to 2015, she voiced one of the main characters in the [[Adult Swim]] animated series ''[[China, IL]]''. In 2011, she was cast as a lead in the [[HBO]] pilot ''The Corrections'', which however was not picked up to series.<ref name=\"Brockes\" /> In 2012, Gerwig appeared in [[Woody Allen]]'s film ''[[To Rome with Love (film)|To Rome with Love]]'' in the vignette ''John's Story'', acting alongside [[Jesse Eisenberg]], and [[Alec Baldwin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/review-to-rome-with-love/|title= Review: To Rome with Love| website= Film Comment|accessdate= April 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Greta Gerwig at TIFF 2014.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Gerwig at the [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\nGerwig and Baumbach co-wrote his next film, ''[[Frances Ha]]'', which was released in May 2013 after having toured the festival circuit since September 2012. Gerwig played the title role, and received a nomination for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical]] for her performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2013/12/12/golden-globes-frances-ha-greta-gerwig/ |title=Golden Globes: 'Frances Ha' star Greta Gerwig is 'just very happy right now. I can't make sense!' |last=Strecker |first=Erin |date=December 12, 2013 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref> Her third collaboration with Baumbach, ''[[Mistress America]],'' was released in August 2015 to generally positive reviews. It holds score of 75 out of 100 at [[Metacritic]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/mistress-america |title=Mistress America |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref> and has an 82% approval rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mistress_america/ |title=Mistress America |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Gerwig made her stage debut as Becky in [[Penelope Skinner]]'s ''[[The Village Bike]]'' at the [[Lucille Lortel Theatre]] in [[New York (state)|New York]]. The show ran until the end of June.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadway.com/shows/village-bike/ |title=The Village Bike - Off-Broadway Tickets - Broadway - Broadway.com |publisher=Broadway.com |accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> She was nominated for the [[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Best Actress for her performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lortel.org/Archives/Production/5628 |title=The Village Bike \u2013 Lortel Archives |publisher=[[Lortel Archives]] |accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> She was cast in the lead role in a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'' titled ''How I Met Your Dad'' in 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/02/greta-gerwig-to-topline-cbs-how-i-met-your-mother-spinoff/ |title=Greta Gerwig To Topline CBS' 'How I Met Your Mother' Spinoff \u2013 Deadline |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=February 11, 2014 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> but it was not picked up to series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/10/greta-gerwig-director-lady-bird.html |title=Greta Gerwig Is a Director, Not a Muse |last=Malone |first=Noreen |date=October 31, 2017 |work=Vulture |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGerwig's next starring role was in [[Rebecca Miller]]'s ''[[Maggie's Plan]]'', which premiered as an official selection of the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/toronto-world-premieres-for-trumbo-demolition-the-program/5090990.article?blocktitle=LATEST-FILM-NEWS&contentID=40562# |title=Toronto to open with 'Demolition'; world premieres for 'Trumbo', 'The Program' |last=Kay |first=Jeremy |date=July 28, 2015 |work=Screen Daily |accessdate=February 19, 2016}}</ref> opening to positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/film-review-greta-gerwig-in-maggies-plan-1201592361/ |title=Sundance Film Review: 'Maggie's Plan' |last=Harvey |first=Dennis |date=September 12, 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/09/maggies-plan-julianne-moore-toronto-review |title=Julianne Moore Shows Off Her Delightful Comedy Chops in Maggie's Plan |last=Lawson |first=Richard |date=September 13, 2015 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=February 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/sep/13/maggies-plan-review-julianne-moore-steals-agreeably-messy-comedy |title=Maggie's Plan review: Julianne Moore steals agreeably messy comedy |last=Smith |first=Nigel M. |date=September 13, 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=February 19, 2016 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The film was also screened at the [[2016 Sundance Film Festival]] and the [[66th Berlin International Film Festival]]. That same year, Gerwig starred in [[Pablo Larra\u00edn]]'s ''[[Jackie (2016 film)|Jackie]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/greta-gerwig-natalie-portman-jackie-1201630585/ |title=Greta Gerwig Joins Natalie Portman in 'Jackie' (EXCLUSIVE) |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=October 30, 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> and [[Mike Mills (director)|Mike Mills]]' ''[[20th Century Women]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/annette-bening-greta-gerwig-elle-fanning-20th-century-women-1201496066/ |title=Annette Bening, Greta Gerwig, Elle Fanning Join '20th Century Women' |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=May 14, 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> earning acclaim for both performances, particularly her work in the latter, for which she earned a nomination for the [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nIn 2016, she guest-starred in two episodes of the comedy series ''[[The Mindy Project]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/18/mindy-project-greta-gerwig-guest-star |title=Greta Gerwig to guest-star on The Mindy Project |last=Bacle |first=Ariana |date=March 18, 2016 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: Critical recognition===\nIn 2017, Gerwig made her solo directorial debut (after having co-directed ''Nights and Weekends'') with the coming-of-age comedy-drama film ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'', which she also wrote.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-directing-debut-iac-films-1201494105/ |title=Greta Gerwig To Direct Her Script 'Lady Bird' For IAC Films |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |date=August 7, 2015 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref> The film's cast includes [[Saoirse Ronan]], [[Laurie Metcalf]], [[Tracy Letts]], [[Lucas Hedges]], [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[Beanie Feldstein]], [[Stephen McKinley Henderson]], and [[Lois Smith]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/john-karna-lady-bird-natasha-liu-bordizzo-hotel-mumbai-1201814887/ |title=John Karna Joins 'Lady Bird' Bevy; Natasha Liu Bordizzo Checks Into 'Hotel Mumbai' |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=September 7, 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> ''Lady Bird'' premiered at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] and was theatrically released in November 2017. The film grossed over $78 million against its $10 million budget worldwide.[[File:Greta Gerwig at the 2018 Berlin Film Festival (1).jpg|thumb|upright|Gerwig at a press conference for ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]'' in 2018]]\n\nUpon its release, ''Lady Bird'' received widespread critical acclaim, with reviewers particularly lauding Gerwig's screenplay and direction.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lady-bird-review-1035669 |title='Lady Bird': Film Review {{!}} Telluride 2017 |last=McCarthy |first=Todd |date=September 5, 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=September 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-1202546609/ |title=Telluride Film Review: Saoirse Ronan in 'Lady Bird' |last=Debruge |first=Peter |date=September 4, 2017 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 8, 2017}}</ref> The film was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]], the [[American Film Institute]], and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine as one of the top ten films of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFI-Awards-2017.aspx |title=AFI Awards 2017 |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208174824/http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFI-Awards-2017.aspx |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"NBR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2017/11/national-board-review-announces-2017-award-winners/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2017 Award Winners |date=November 28, 2017 |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/5045566/top-10-movies-2017/ |title=The Top 10 Movies of 2017 |last=Zacharek |first=Stephanie |date=December 7, 2017 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> According to the review-aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], it was given 196 positive reviews in a row, making it the record-holder for the most \"fresh\" reviews,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biography.com/people/greta-gerwig-21430131 |title=Greta Gerwig Biography |publisher=Biography.com |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> until the first \"rotten\" one arrived in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/lady-bird-rotten-tomatoes-record-broken-bad-review-cole-smithey-1201906394/ |title='Lady Bird' No Longer Has a Perfect 100% on Rotten Tomatoes (and Nobody is Happy About It) |last=Sharf |first=Zack |date=December 11, 2017 |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> It currently has a 99% rating on the aforementioned website.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lady_bird |title=Lady Bird |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], ''Lady Bird'' won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for [[Saoirse Ronan]], and also received nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] for [[Laurie Metcalf]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] for Gerwig. At the [[90th Academy Awards]], it was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Gerwig, [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Ronan, and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for Metcalf. With the nominations announced, Gerwig became the fifth woman in Oscar history to be nominated for Best Director.<ref name=\"Gonzalez\" /> When she found out about the nominations, Gerwig said she was \"in various states of laughing and crying and yelling with joy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hellogiggles.com/news/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-crying-oscar-nominations/ |title=Greta Gerwig can't stop crying about \"Lady Bird's\" Oscar nominations, and the feelings are real |last=Cord-Cruz |first=Nicole |date=January 23, 2018 |publisher=[[HelloGiggles]] |accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, following the success of ''Lady Bird'', Gerwig was part of the voice cast of [[Wes Anderson]]'s stop-motion animated film ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]'', which premiered at the [[68th Berlin International Film Festival]] to critical acclaim, and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/festivals/berlin-film-festival-wes-anderson-bill-murry-isle-of-dogs-1202700960/ |title=Berlin Opening Night: Wes Anderson, Tilda Swinton, Greta Gerwig Celebrate 'Isle of Dogs' |last=Meza |first=Ed |date=February 15, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, it was announced that Gerwig would direct a new [[Little Women (2019 film)|film adaptation]] of [[Louisa May Alcott]]'s novel ''[[Little Women]]'', whose script she had been previously hired to write. With an ensemble cast featuring [[Saoirse Ronan]], [[Emma Watson]], [[Florence Pugh]], [[Eliza Scanlen]], [[Laura Dern]], [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], and [[Meryl Streep]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/06/greta-gerwig-little-women-saoirse-ronan-timothee-chalamet-stone-streep-1201979912/ |title=Director Greta Gerwig Eyeing 'Little Women' With Saoirse Ronan, Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet, Emma Stone, and Meryl Streep |last=Sharf |first=Zack |date=June 29, 2018 |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/972647-emma-watson-replacing-emma-stone-in-sonys-little-women-movie |title=Emma Watson Replacing Emma Stone in Sony's Little Women Movie |last=Spencer |first=Perry |date=August 24, 2018 |publisher=ComingSoon.net |accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/laura-dern-talks-join-meryl-streep-little-women-1132076 |title=Laura Dern in Talks to Join Meryl Streep in 'Little Women' (Exclusive) |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |date=August 14, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref> ''Little Women'' was released in December 2019 to widespread critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/quentin-tarantino-zombieland-2-little-women-white-boy-rick-sony-release-dates-1202429051/ |title=Sony Moves Tarantino's Manson Pic, Dates 'Zombieland 2' & 'Little Women' |last=Pederson |first=Erik |date=July 18, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> At the [[92nd Academy Awards]], it received six nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Ronan, [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for Pugh, and [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] for Gerwig,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/greta-gerwigs-adaptation-brings-little-women-oscar-noms-tally-14-1268988|title=Oscars: Greta Gerwig's Adaptation Brings 'Little Women' Noms Tally to 14|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> and a win for [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]. The film was frequently mentioned as part of an Oscars controversy after no woman (including Gerwig) was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], a snub that was publicly noted by [[Hillary Clinton]] and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', amongst others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/greta-gerwig-oscars-directing-snub-little-women-1203491117/|title=Greta Gerwig on \u2018Little Women\u2019s\u2019 Oscar Nominations \u2014 and That One Big Snub|last=Aurthur|first=Kate|last2=Aurthur|first2=Kate|date=2020-02-04|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> Gerwig's name was one of those featured on the cape that actress [[Natalie Portman]] wore to the ceremony, which featured the names of snubbed female directors from that year's ceremony.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marriott|first=Hannah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2020/feb/10/fashion-statements-oscars-stars-natalie-portman-waad-al-kateab|title=Fashion statements: Oscars stars use their clothes to make political points|date=2020-02-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n====Upcoming projects====\nGerwig will collaborate with Baumbach in co-writing and potentially directing a live-action ''[[Barbie (film series)|Barbie]]'' film, starring [[Margot Robbie]] in the title role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/greta-gerwig-noah-baumbach-write-margot-robbie-barbie-movie-1196005|title=Greta Gerwig, Noah Baumbach to Tackle Margot Robbie-Produced 'Barbie' Movie|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first1=Borys|last1=Kit|first2=Mia|last2=Galuppo|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Directing style==\nGerwig's films tend to be based on her own experiences. In a behind-the-scenes video on the set of ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'' she said, \"I tend to start with things from my own life, then pretty quickly they spin out into their own orbit.\"<ref name=\"Realizing Lady Bird\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xT23PMOSnAk&t=3s |title=Realizing Lady Bird |date=February 28, 2018 |accessdate=April 6, 2018}}{{dead link|date=March 2019}}</ref> Gerwig presses her actors to incorporate their personalities into their performances as well, and says of her writing and directing, \"it's all about actors.\"<ref name=\"Realizing Lady Bird\"/> In addition, she allows little line [[improvisation]] and the script is followed fairly closely.<ref name=\"Smallwood\"/>\n\nHer works have common themes: the growth and emotional maturation of the leading woman, and relationships among family members, friends, and significant others, with a special interest in female dynamics. Characters are reportedly never villainized, and all are sympathetic. She tends to imbue her films with a unique and specific deadpan sense of humor. Visually they also carry a very specific atmosphere \u2013 simultaneously having the warmth of looking back on something in memory and displaying things as they are, stripped of any sort of showiness.<ref name=\"Smallwood\" /><ref name=\"Realizing Lady Bird\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nGerwig moved to [[New York City]] at 19 to attend [[Barnard College]]. She lives in [[Brooklyn]] with filmmaker [[Noah Baumbach]], her partner since late 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/07/entertainment/la-et-mn-frances-ha-greta-gerwig-noah-baumbach-20120908 |title='Frances Ha' bonds Noah Baumbach, Greta Gerwig |last=Olsen |first=Mark |date=September 7, 2012 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2013/04/29/130429fa_fact_parker |title=Happiness |last=Parker |first=Ian |date=April 29, 2013 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> In March 2019, it was announced Gerwig had given birth to their son Harold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1025007/surprise-greta-gerwig-and-noah-baumbach-welcomed-their-first-child|title=Surprise! Greta Gerwig and Noah Baumbach Welcomed Their First Child|website=[[E! News]]|first=Jess|last=Cohen|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/greta-gerwig-and-boyfriend-noah-baumbach-secretly-welcome-baby-boy/|title=Greta Gerwig and Boyfriend Noah Baumbach Secretly Welcome Baby Boy|website=[[US Weekly]]|first=Emily|last=Marcus|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/greta-gerwig-cover-january-2020|title=Greta Gerwig on the Twin Adventures of Filmmaking and Motherhood\n|first=Chloe|last=Malle|magazine=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|accessdate=December 6, 2019|date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n'''As a Director''' \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n!width=65| Director\n!width=65| Writer\n!width=65| Producer\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Nights and Weekends]]'' || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || Feature directorial debut <br> co-director [[Joe Swanberg]]\n|-\n|2017 || ''[[Lady Bird]]'' || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{no}} ||\n|-\n|2019 || ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]'' || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{no}} ||\n|-\n|}\n\n'''As an Actress'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Director \n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[LOL (2006 film)|LOL]]''\n| Greta\n| rowspan=2|[[Joe Swanberg]] \n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Hannah Takes the Stairs]]''\n| Hannah\n| Also co-writer\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Baghead]]''\n| Michelle\n| [[Mark Duplass]] <br/> [[Jay Duplass]]\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Yeast''\n| Gen\n| Mary Bronstein\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Nights and Weekends]]''\n| Mattie\n| [[Joe Swanberg]] <br/> Greta Gerwig\n| Feature directorial debut <br> Also co-writer, co-director, co-producer\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Quick Feet, Soft Hands''\n| Lisa\n| Paul Harrin \n| Short film\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''I Thought You Finally Completely Lost It''\n| Greta\n| [[Rod Webber]] \n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''You Wont Miss Me''\n| Bridget\n| [[Ry Russo-Young]] \n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The House of the Devil]]''\n| Megan\n|[[Ti West]]\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Greenberg (film)|Greenberg]]''\n| Florence Marr\n| [[Noah Baumbach]] \n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Art House''\n| Nora Ohr\n| Victor Fanucchi\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Northern Comfort]]''\n| Cassandra\n| [[Rod Webber]] \n| Also co-writer\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Dish & the Spoon]]''\n| Rose\n| Alison Bagnall\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]''\n| Patrice\n| [[Ivan Reitman]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Damsels in Distress (film)|Damsels in Distress]]''\n| Violet Wister\n| [[Whit Stillman]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Arthur (2011 film)|Arthur]]''\n| Naomi Quinn\n| [[Jason Winer]] \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Lola Versus]]''\n| Lola\n| [[Daryl Wein]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[To Rome with Love (film)|To Rome with Love]]''\n| Sally\n| [[Woody Allen]] \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Frances Ha]]''\n| Frances Halladay\n| [[Noah Baumbach]]\n| Also co-writer\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Eden (2014 French film)|Eden]]''\n| Julia\n| [[Mia Hansen-L\u00f8ve]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Humbling (film)|The Humbling]]''\n| Pegeen Mike Stapleford\n| [[Barry Levinson]] \n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Mistress America]]''\n| Brooke Cardinas\n| [[Noah Baumbach]]\n| Also co-writer and co-producer\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Maggie's Plan]]''\n| Maggie Hardin\n| [[Rebecca Miller]] \n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Wiener-Dog (film)|Wiener-Dog]]''\n| Dawn Wiener\n| [[Todd Solondz]] \n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Jackie (2016 film)|Jackie]]''\n| [[Nancy Tuckerman]]\n| [[Pablo Larra\u00edn]]\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[20th Century Women]]''\n| Abigail Porter\n| [[Mike Mills (director)|Mike Mills]]\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories]]''\n| Victoria (voice)\n| [[Noah Baumbach]]\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Isle of Dogs (film)|Isle of Dogs]]''\n| Tracy Walker (voice)\n| [[Wes Anderson]] \n|\n|-\n|} \n<!--DO NOT USE ROWSPANS PER WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n<!-- Per WP:NFF and WP:CRYSTAL, do not add films that are listed as \"pre-production\" -->\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2011\u201315\n| ''[[China, IL]]''\n| Pony Merks (voice)\n| 21 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''The Corrections''\n| Julia Vrais\n| Unaired [[HBO]] pilot\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''How I Met Your Dad''\n| Sally\n| Unaired [[CBS]] pilot\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Portlandia (TV series)|Portlandia]]''\n| Mermaid\n| Episode: \"Doug Becomes a Feminist\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Mindy Project]]''\n| Sarah Branum\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Ms. Reynolds\n| Uncredited; Episode: \"[[Saoirse Ronan]]/[[U2]]\"\n|}\n\n== Theatre ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Venue\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2014 || ''[[The Village Bike]]'' || Becky || [[MCC Theater]], Off-Broadway || rowspan=2|<ref>https://www.broadwayworld.com/people/Greta-Gerwig/</ref>\n|-\n|2020 || ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' || Performer || [[New York Theatre Workshop]], Off-Broadway\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Greta Gerwig}}\n\nIn 2011, Gerwig won an award from the [[Athena Film Festival]] for her artistry as one of [[Hollywood]]'s definitive screen actresses of her generation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://athenafilmfestival.com/awards/award-winners/2011-athena-award-winners/ |title=2011 Athena Award Winners |publisher=[[Athena Film Festival]] |accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, she was selected as a member of the jury for the [[64th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/01/james-schamus-will-head-berlin-jury-that-includes-christoph-waltz-greta-gerwig-and-michel-gondry-31370/ |title=James Schamus Will Head Berlin Jury That Includes Christoph Waltz, Greta Gerwig and Michel Gondry |date=January 14, 2014 |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, her nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] at the [[90th Academy Awards]] for ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'' made her the first woman in eight years (and one of only five women in Oscar history) to have been nominated in that category.<ref name=\"Gonzalez\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/oscars-greta-gerwig-gets-first-female-director-nod-in-eight-years-11219567 |title=Oscars 2018: Greta Gerwig gets first female director nomination in eight years |date=January 23, 2018 |publisher=[[Sky News]] |accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Gerwig's work on ''Lady Bird'' was nominated for sixteen awards in notable circuits, winning six of those awards.<ref name=\"NBR\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/golden-globes-2018-lady-bird-wins-best-motion-picture-musical-or-comedy/ |title=Golden Globes 2018: Lady Bird Wins Best Motion Picture, Musical or Comedy |last=Wicks |first=Amanda |date=January 8, 2018 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=March 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/national-society-film-critics-winners-2018-list-full-1072167 |title='Lady Bird' Named Best Picture by National Society of Film Critics |last=Lewis |first=Hilary |date=January 6, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of female film and television directors]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister links|d=Q271967|c=Category:Greta Gerwig|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|q=no}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Greta Gerwig|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Greta Gerwig|Awards for Greta Gerwig]]\n| list =\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gerwig, Greta}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American Unitarian Universalists]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Barnard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLadybird (disambiguation)(link changed toLady Bird (film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greta_Gerwig"}
{"title_page": "Martine Wonner", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{ infobox Politician\n| name        = Martine Wonner\n| image       = Martine Wonner par Claude Truong-Ngoc juillet 2017.jpg\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br>for [[Bas-Rhin's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = Sophie Rohfritsch\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1964|3|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hayange]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n}}\n'''Martine Wonner''' (born 27 March 1964) is a French politician of [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who has been serving as a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] since the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 elections]], representing the [[Bas-Rhin's 4th constituency|4th constituency]] of the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Bas-Rhin]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/067/06704.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nWonner graduated in psychiatric medicine from the [[University of Strasbourg]]. She began her career as a medical consultant for the Agence R\u00e9gionale de l'Hospitalisation of Lorraine and Alsace and then joined the private group Ramsay G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Sant\u00e9 in 2006. She then worked as a psychiatrist in a specialised clinic, before taking up managerial positions, first for [[SAMU Social]] and then for the private medical group Sinou\u00e9.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|title=L\u00e9gislatives : qui est Martine Wonner, la nouvelle d\u00e9put\u00e9e REM de la 4e circonscription du Bas-Rhin ?|website=[[France Bleu]]|date=18 June 2017|url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/politique/legislatives-qui-est-martine-wonner-la-nouvelle-deputee-rem-de-la-4e-circonscription-du-bas-rhin-1497621242|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>.\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Wonner serves on the Committee on Social Affairs.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA722268 Martine Wonner] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref> In addition to her role in parliament, she has been serving as member of the French delegation to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] since 2017. She is a member of the Sub-Committee on Children.<ref>[http://www.assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/AssemblyList/MP-Details-EN.asp?MemberID=8055 Martine Wonner] [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]].</ref> \n\n==Political positions==\nIn April 2018, Wonner joined other co-signatories around [[S\u00e9bastien Nadot]] in officially filing a request for a commission of inquiry into the legality of French weapons sales to the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition fighting in Yemen]], days before an official visit of [[Saudi Crown Prince]] [[Mohammed bin Salman]] to Paris.<ref>John Irish and Marine Pennetier (5 April 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-saudi-arms/ahead-of-saudi-prince-visit-macron-lawmaker-asks-for-inquiry-over-french-arms-sales-idUSKCN1HC2N9 Ahead of Saudi prince visit, Macron lawmaker asks for inquiry over French arms sales] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Wonner co-sponsored an initiative in favour of legalizing [[assisted reproductive technology]] (ART) for all women (singles, heterosexual couples or lesbian couples).<ref>[https://www.liberation.fr/debats/2018/05/29/la-pma-pour-toutes-un-acte-d-egalite_1655111 La PMA pour toutes, un acte d\u2019\u00e9galit\u00e9] ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'', 29 May 2018.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Wonner decided not to align with her parliamentary group\u2019s majority and became one of 52 LREM members who abstained from a vote on the French ratification of the [[European Union]]\u2019s [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA) with [[Canada]].<ref>Maxime Vaudano (24 July 2019), [https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/07/24/ceta-qui-a-vote-quoi-parmi-les-deputes_5493039_4355770.html CETA : qui a vot\u00e9 quoi parmi les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wonner, Martine}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{ infobox Politician\n| name        = Martine Wonner\n| image       = Martine Wonner par Claude Truong-Ngoc juillet 2017.jpg\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br>for [[Bas-Rhin's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = Sophie Rohfritsch\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1964|3|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hayange]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n}}\n'''Martine Wonner''' (born 27 March 1964) is a French politician of [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who has been serving as a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] since the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 elections]], representing the [[Bas-Rhin's 4th constituency|4th constituency]] of the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Bas-Rhin]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/067/06704.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nWonner graduated in psychiatric medicine from the [[University of Strasbourg]]. She began her career as a medical consultant for the Agence R\u00e9gionale de l'Hospitalisation of Lorraine and Alsace and then joined the private group Ramsay G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Sant\u00e9 in 2006. She then worked as a psychiatrist in a specialised clinic, before taking up managerial positions, first for [[SAMU Social]] and then for the private medical group Sinou\u00e9.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|title=L\u00e9gislatives : qui est Martine Wonner, la nouvelle d\u00e9put\u00e9e REM de la 4e circonscription du Bas-Rhin ?|website=[[France Bleu]]|date=18 June 2017|url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/politique/legislatives-qui-est-martine-wonner-la-nouvelle-deputee-rem-de-la-4e-circonscription-du-bas-rhin-1497621242|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>.\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Wonner serves on the Committee on Social Affairs.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA722268 Martine Wonner] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref> In addition to her role in parliament, she has been serving as member of the French delegation to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] since 2017. She is a member of the Sub-Committee on Children.<ref>[http://www.assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/AssemblyList/MP-Details-EN.asp?MemberID=8055 Martine Wonner] [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]].</ref> \n\n==Political positions==\nIn April 2018, Wonner joined other co-signatories around [[S\u00e9bastien Nadot]] in officially filing a request for a commission of inquiry into the legality of French weapons sales to the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition fighting in Yemen]], days before an official visit of [[Saudi Crown Prince]] [[Mohammed bin Salman]] to Paris.<ref>John Irish and Marine Pennetier (April 5, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-saudi-arms/ahead-of-saudi-prince-visit-macron-lawmaker-asks-for-inquiry-over-french-arms-sales-idUSKCN1HC2N9 Ahead of Saudi prince visit, Macron lawmaker asks for inquiry over French arms sales] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Wonner co-sponsored an initiative in favour of legalizing [[assisted reproductive technology]] (ART) for all women (singles, heterosexual couples or lesbian couples).<ref>[https://www.liberation.fr/debats/2018/05/29/la-pma-pour-toutes-un-acte-d-egalite_1655111 La PMA pour toutes, un acte d\u2019\u00e9galit\u00e9] ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'', 29 May 2018.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Wonner decided not to align with her parliamentary group\u2019s majority and became one of 52 LREM members who abstained from a vote on the French ratification of the [[European Union]]\u2019s [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA) with [[Canada]].<ref>Maxime Vaudano (24 July 2019), [https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/07/24/ceta-qui-a-vote-quoi-parmi-les-deputes_5493039_4355770.html CETA : qui a vot\u00e9 quoi parmi les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wonner, Martine}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martine_Wonner"}
{"title_page": "Satellite constellation", "text_new": "[[File:GPS satellite constellation.jpg|thumb|240px|The [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] constellation calls for 24 satellites to be distributed equally among six [[orbital plane (astronomy)|orbital planes]]]]\nA '''satellite constellation''' is a group of [[artificial satellite]]s working together as a system. Unlike a single satellite, a constellation can provide permanent global or near-global [[pass (spaceflight)|coverage]], such that at any time everywhere on Earth at least one satellite is visible. Satellites are typically placed in sets of complementary [[orbital plane (astronomy)|orbital planes]] and connect to globally distributed [[ground station]]s. They may also use [[Inter-satellite service|inter-satellite communication]].\n\nSatellite constellations should not be confused with ''satellite clusters'', which are groups of satellites moving very close together in almost identical orbits (see [[satellite formation flying]]), ''satellite programs'' (such as [[Landsat program|Landsat]]), which are generations of satellites launched in succession, and ''satellite fleets'', which are groups of satellites from the same manufacturer or operator that function independently from each other (not as a system).\n\n== Overview ==\n[[File:Flare at Paranal.jpg|thumb|A bright artificial satellite flare is visible above the [[Very Large Telescope|VLT]]. Satellite constellations have an impact on ground-based astronomy.<ref>{{cite web |title=On the increasing number of satellite constellations |url=https://www.eso.org/public/announcements/ann19029/ |website=www.eso.org |accessdate=10 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>]]\n\n[[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth orbiting satellites]] (LEOs) are often deployed in satellite constellations, because the coverage area provided by a single LEO satellite only covers a small area that moves as the satellite travels at the high [[angular velocity]] needed to maintain its [[Planetary orbit|orbit]].  Many LEO satellites are needed to maintain continuous coverage over an area. This contrasts with [[geostationary]] satellites, where a single satellite, moving at the same angular velocity as the rotation of the Earth's surface, provides permanent coverage over a large area.\n\nExamples of satellite constellations include the [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS), [[Galileo positioning system|Galileo]] and [[GLONASS]] constellations for [[navigation]] and [[geodesy]], the [[Iridium (satellite)|Iridium]] and [[Globalstar]] satellite telephony services, the [[Disaster Monitoring Constellation]] and [[RapidEye]] for remote sensing, the [[Orbcomm]] messaging service, Russian [[elliptic orbit]] [[Molniya (satellite)|Molniya]] and Tundra constellations, the large-scale [[Teledesic]], Skybridge, and [[Celestri]] [[broadband]] constellation proposals of the 1990s, and more recent systems such as [[O3b]] or the [[OneWeb]] proposal.\n\nFor applications which benefit from low-latency [[telecommunication|communications]], LEO satellite constellations provide an advantage over a geostationary satellite, where minimum theoretical latency from ground to satellite is about 125 milliseconds, compared to 1\u20134 milliseconds for a LEO satellite.  A LEO satellite constellation can also provide more system capacity by frequency reuse across its coverage, with [[spot beam]] frequency use being analogous to the minimum number of satellites needed to provide a service, and their orbits\u2014is a field in itself.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Walker Constellation ===\n\nThere are a large number of constellations that may satisfy a particular mission. Usually constellations are designed so that the satellites have similar orbits, eccentricity and inclination so that any perturbations affect each satellite in approximately the same way. In this way, the geometry can be preserved without excessive station-keeping thereby reducing the fuel usage and hence increasing the life of the satellites. Another consideration is that the phasing of each satellite in an orbital plane maintains sufficient separation to avoid collisions or interference at orbit plane intersections. Circular orbits are popular, because then the satellite is at a constant altitude requiring a constant strength signal to communicate.\n\nA class of circular orbit geometries that has become popular is the Walker Delta Pattern constellation.\nThis has an associated notation to describe it which was proposed by John Walker.<ref>J. G. Walker, Satellite constellations, Journal of the British Interplanetary Society, vol. 37, pp. 559-571, 1984</ref> His notation is:\n\n:::'''i: t/p/f'''\n\nwhere:\n'''i''' is the inclination;\n'''t''' is the total number of satellites;\n'''p''' is the number of equally spaced planes; and\n'''f''' is the relative spacing between satellites in adjacent planes. The change in true anomaly (in degrees) for equivalent satellites in neighbouring planes is equal to '''f'''*360/'''t'''.\n\nFor example, the [[Galileo (satellite navigation)|Galileo Navigation system]] is a Walker Delta 56\u00b0:24/3/1 constellation. This means there are 24 satellites in 3 planes inclined at 56 degrees, spanning the 360 degrees around the [[equator]]. The \"1\" defines the phasing between the planes, and how they are spaced. The Walker Delta is also known as the Ballard rosette, after A. H. Ballard's similar earlier work.<ref>A. H. Ballard, Rosette Constellations of Earth Satellites, IEEE Transactions on Aerospace and Electronic Systems, Vol 16 No. 5, Sep. 1980.</ref><ref>J. G. Walker, Comments on \"Rosette constellations of earth satellites\", IEEE Transactions on Aerospace and Electronic Systems, vol. 18 no. 4, pp. 723-724,\nNovember 1982.</ref> Ballard's notation is (t,p,m) where m is a multiple of the fractional offset between planes.\n\nAnother popular constellation type is the near-polar Walker Star, which is used by [[Iridium (satellite)|Iridium]]. Here, the satellites are in near-polar circular orbits across approximately 180 degrees, travelling north on one side of the Earth, and south on the other.  The active satellites in the full Iridium constellation form a Walker Star of 86.4\u00b0:66/6/2, i.e. the phasing repeats every two planes. Walker uses similar notation for stars and deltas, which can be confusing.\n\nThese sets of circular orbits at constant altitude are sometimes referred to as [[orbital shell (spaceflight)|orbital shells]].\n\n=== Broadband ===\nIn 2015 Farooq Khan then the President of [[Samsung Research America]] published a research paper providing details how a large satellite broadband constellation can be designed.<ref>{{cite arxiv|last1=Khan|first1=Farooq|title=Mobile Internet from the Heavens|eprint=1508.02383|date=9 August 2015|class=cs.NI}}</ref>\n\n== List of satellite constellations ==\n\n=== Navigational satellite constellations ===\n{{Main article|Satellite navigation}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Satellite constellations used for navigation\n!Name\n!Operator\n!Satellites and orbits\n(latest design, excluding spares)\n!Coverage\n!Service(s)\n!Status\n!Years in service\n|-\n|[[Global Positioning System]] (GPS)\n|[[United States Space Force|USSF]]\n|24 in 6 planes at 20,180 km (55\u00b0 MEO) \n|Global\n|Navigation\n|Operational\n|1993-\n|-\n|[[GLONASS]]\n|[[Roscosmos]]\n|24 in 3 planes at 19,130 km (64\u00b08' MEO)\n|Global\n|Navigation\n|Operational\n|1995-\n|-\n|[[Galileo (satellite navigation)|Galileo]]\n|[[European GNSS Agency|GSA]], [[European Space Agency|ESA]]\n|24 in 3 planes at 23,222 km (56\u00b0 MEO)\n|Global\n|Navigation\n|Operational\n|2019-\n|-\n|[[BeiDou]]\n|[[China National Space Administration|CNSA]]\n|3 geostationary at 35,786 km (GEO)\n3 in 3 planes at 35,786 km (55\u00b0 GSO)\n\n24 in 3 planes at 21,150 km (55\u00b0 MEO)\n|Regional\nGlobal\n|Navigation\n|Operational\n|2012- (Asia)\n2018- (Globally)\n|-\n|[[NAVIC]]\n|[[ISRO]]\n|3 geostationary at 35,786 km (GEO)\n4 in 2 planes at 250-24,000 km (29\u0