{"title_page": "Waverley Novels", "text_new": "{{short description|Long series of novels by Sir Walter Scott}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2010}}\n[[Image:Ivanhoe (opera).jpg|right|thumb|300px|Scenes from the ''[[Illustrated London News]]'' of [[Arthur Sullivan]]'s operatic adaptation of [[Ivanhoe (opera)|Ivanhoe]].]]\n\nThe '''Waverley Novels''' are a long series of novels by Sir [[Walter Scott]] (1771\u20131832). For nearly a century, they were among the most popular and widely read novels in all of Europe.\n\nBecause Scott did not publicly acknowledge authorship until 1827, the series takes its name from ''[[Waverley (novel)|Waverley]]'', the first novel of the series released in 1814. The later books bore the words \"by the author of [[Waverley (novel)|''Waverley'']]\" on their title pages.\n\nThe ''[[Tales of my Landlord]]'' sub-series was not advertised as \"by the author of ''Waverley''\" and thus is not always included as part of the Waverley Novels series.\n\n==Order of publication==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Title !! Published !! Main setting !! Period\n|-\n|''[[Waverley (novel)|Waverley]]'', or, '''Tis Sixty Years Since'' || 1814 || [[Perthshire]] (Scotland)|| 1745\u20131746\n|-\n|''[[Guy Mannering]]'', or, ''The Astrologer'' || 1815 || [[Galloway]] (Scotland)|| 1760-5, 1781\u20132\n|-\n|''[[The Antiquary]]'' || 1816 || North-East Scotland || 1790s\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 1st series:\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Black Dwarf (novel)|The Black Dwarf]]'' || 1816 || [[Scottish Borders]] || 1707\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Tale of Old Mortality]]'' || 1816 || Southern Scotland || 1679\u201389\n|-\n|''[[Rob Roy (novel)|Rob Roy]]'' || 1818 || [[Northumberland]] (England), and the environs of [[Loch Lomond]] (Scotland) || 1715\u201316\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 2nd series:\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Heart of Midlothian]]'' || 1818 || [[Edinburgh]] and [[Richmond, London]] || 1736\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 3rd series:\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Bride of Lammermoor]]'' || 1819 || [[East Lothian]] (Scotland) || 1709\u201311\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[A Legend of Montrose]]'' || 1819 || [[Scottish Highlands]] || 1644-5\n|-\n|''[[Ivanhoe]]'' || 1819 || [[Yorkshire]], [[Nottinghamshire]] and [[Leicestershire]] (England)|| 1194\n|-\n|''[[The Monastery]]'' || 1820 || [[Scottish Borders]] || 1547\u201357\n|-\n|''[[The Abbot]]'' || 1820 || Various in Scotland || 1567-8\n|-\n|''[[Kenilworth (novel)|Kenilworth]]'' || 1821 || [[Berkshire]] and [[Warwickshire]] (England) || 1575\n|-\n|''[[The Pirate (novel)|The Pirate]]'' || 1822 || [[Shetland]] and [[Orkney]] || 1690s\n|-\n|''[[The Fortunes of Nigel]]'' || 1822 || [[London]] and [[Greenwich]] (England)|| 1616\u201318\n|-\n|''[[Peveril of the Peak]]'' || 1822 || [[Derbyshire]], the [[Isle of Man]], and [[London]] || 1658\u201380\n|-\n|''[[Quentin Durward]]'' || 1823 || [[Tours]] and [[P\u00e9ronne, Somme|P\u00e9ronne]] (France)<br>[[Li\u00e8ge]] ([[Wallonia]]/Belgium) || 1468\n|-\n|''[[St. Ronan's Well]]'' || 1824 || Southern Scotland || 19th century\n|-\n|''[[Redgauntlet]]'' || 1824 || Southern Scotland, and [[Cumberland]] (England)|| 1766\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of the Crusaders'':\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Betrothed (Scott novel)|The Betrothed]]'' || 1825 || Wales, and [[Gloucester]] (England)|| 1187\u201392\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Talisman (Scott novel)|The Talisman]]'' || 1825 || [[Syria]] || 1191\n|-\n|''[[Woodstock (novel)|Woodstock]]'', or, ''The Cavalier'' || 1826 || [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire|Woodstock]] and [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]] (England)<br>[[Brussels]], in the [[Spanish Netherlands]] || 1652\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Chronicles of the Canongate'', 2nd series:<ref>The first series of ''Chronicles of the Canongate'' contained two short stories ('The Highland Widow' and 'The Two Drovers'), and a short novel ''The Surgeon's Daughter'', set in the second half of the 18th century, partly in India.</ref>\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''St Valentine's Day'', or, ''[[The Fair Maid of Perth]]'' || 1828 || [[Perthshire]] (Scotland) || 1396\n|-\n|''[[Anne of Geierstein]]'', or, ''The Maiden in the Mist'' || 1829 || Switzerland and Eastern France || 1474\u201377\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of my Landlord'', 4th series:<ref>A further novel, ''The Siege of Malta'', set in the Mediterranean in 1565, and an incomplete novella ''Bizarro'', set in Calabria in the first two decades of the 19th century, were first published in 2008.</ref>\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Count Robert of Paris]]'' || 1831 || [[Constantinople]] and [[\u00dcsk\u00fcdar|Scutari]] (now in [[Turkey]]) || 1097\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Castle Dangerous]]'' || 1831 || [[Lanarkshire]] (Scotland) || 1307\n\n|}\n\n==Chronological order, by setting==\n*1097: ''Count Robert of Paris''\n*1187\u201394: ''The Betrothed, The Talisman, Ivanhoe'' (3)\n*1307: ''Castle Dangerous''\n*1396: ''The Fair Maid of Perth''\n*1468\u201377: ''Quentin Durward, Anne of Geierstein'' (2)\n*1547\u201375: ''The Monastery, The Abbot, Kenilworth, The Siege of Malta'' (4)\n*1616\u201318: ''The Fortunes of Nigel''\n*1644\u201389: ''A Legend of Montrose, Woodstock, Peveril of the Peak, The Tale of Old Mortality, The Pirate'' (5)\n*1700\u201399: ''The Black Dwarf, The Bride of Lammermoor, Rob Roy, Heart of Midlothian, Waverley, Guy Mannering, Redgauntlet, The Antiquary'' (8)\n*19th century: ''St. Ronan's Well''\n\n==Editions==\nThe novels were all originally printed by [[James Ballantyne]] on [[the Canongate]] in Edinburgh. James Ballantyne was the brother of one of Scott's close friends, [[John Ballantyne (publisher)|John Ballantyne]] (\"Printed by James Ballantyne and Co. for Archibald Constable and Co., Edinburgh\"). \n\nThere are two definitive editions. One is the \"Magnum Opus\", a 48-volume set published between 1829 and 1833 by [[Robert Cadell]], based on previous editions, with new introductions and notes by Scott. This was the basis of almost all subsequent editions until the appearance of the standard modern edition, the [[Edinburgh edition of the Waverley novels|Edinburgh Edition of the Waverley Novels]], a 30-volume set, based on early-edition texts emended mainly from the surviving manuscripts, published by Edinburgh University Press between 1993 and 2012.\n\n==Placenames==\n[[File:Edinburgh-scottm.600px.jpg|right|thumb|View from the [[Scott Monument]] of the [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Waverley Station]] roof, in [[Edinburgh]], with [[Arthur's Seat]] in the background]]\n\nIn Scotland, [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Waverley Station]] and [[Waverley Bridge]] in [[Edinburgh]] were named after these novels.\n\nIn North America, the towns of [[Waverly, Colorado]]; [[Waverly, Nebraska]]; [[Waverly, Illinois]]; [[Waverly, South Dakota]]; [[Waverly, Tioga County, New York|Waverley, New York]]; [[Waverley, Nova Scotia]]; [[Waverly, Ohio]]; [[Waverly Hall, Georgia]];<ref name=\"http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/counties-cities-neighborhoods/harris-county\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/counties-cities-neighborhoods/harris-county |title=Harris County |work=Harris County }}</ref> [[Waverly, Tennessee]],<ref name=\"waverly.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.waverly.net/hcchamber/history.htm |title=History of Humphreys County Tennessee |work=Humphreys County Chamber of Commerce |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516154432/http://www.waverly.net/hcchamber/history.htm |archivedate=May 16, 2007}}</ref>, and [[Waverly, Iowa]], take their names from these novels, as does Waverley School in Louisville, Kentucky, which later became the [[Waverly Hills Sanatorium]].\n\nThe unincorporated community of [[Ellerslie, Georgia]] is believed to be named for a character in the novels, Captain Ellerslie. <ref>http://www.kenkrakow.com/gpn/e.pdf</ref>\n\nIn Australia, the Melbourne suburbs of [[Glen Waverley, Victoria|Glen Waverley]] and [[Mount Waverley, Victoria|Mount Waverley]] and also [[Ivanhoe, Victoria| Ivanhoe]], were named after the novels as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rampantscotland.com/placenames/placename_melbourne.htm |title=Scottish Place Names in Melbourne, Australia |accessdate=23 June 2018 |last=Kendall |first=Ian |date=January 2011 |orig-year=June 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn New Zealand there is a suburb in Dunedin and a North Island town in the province of Taranaki called Waverley.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* ''[[Tales of my Landlord]]''\n* ''[[Tales of the Crusaders]]''\n* ''[[Chronicles of the Canongate]]''\n\n==Notes and references==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* A typically enthusiastic [http://www.oldandsold.com/articles28/books-4.shtml essay] on the Waverley Novels, published in 1912\n\n{{Walter Scott}}\n\n[[Category:Walter Scott novel series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Long series of novels by Sir Walter Scott}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2010}}\n[[Image:Ivanhoe (opera).jpg|right|thumb|300px|Scenes from the ''[[Illustrated London News]]'' of [[Arthur Sullivan]]'s operatic adaptation of [[Ivanhoe (opera)|Ivanhoe]].]]\n\nThe '''Waverley Novels''' are a long series of novels by Sir [[Walter Scott]] (1771\u20131832). For nearly a century, they were among the most popular and widely read novels in all of Europe.\n\nBecause Scott did not publicly acknowledge authorship until 1827, the series takes its name from ''[[Waverley (novel)|Waverley]]'', the first novel of the series released in 1814. The later books bore the words \"by the author of [[Waverley (novel)|''Waverley'']]\" on their title pages.\n\nThe ''[[Tales of my Landlord]]'' sub-series was not advertised as \"by the author of ''Waverley''\" and thus is not always included as part of the Waverley Novels series.\n\n==Order of publication==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Title !! Published !! Main setting !! Period\n|-\n|''[[Waverley (novel)|Waverley]]'', or, '''Tis Sixty Years Since'' || 1814 || [[Perthshire]] (Scotland)|| 1745\u20131746\n|-\n|''[[Guy Mannering]]'', or, ''The Astrologer'' || 1815 || [[Galloway]] (Scotland)|| 1760-5, 1781\u20132\n|-\n|''[[The Antiquary]]'' || 1816 || North-East Scotland || 1790s\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 1st series:\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Black Dwarf (novel)|The Black Dwarf]]'' || 1816 || [[Scottish Borders]] || 1707\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Tale of Old Mortality]]'' || 1816 || Southern Scotland || 1679\u201389\n|-\n|''[[Rob Roy (novel)|Rob Roy]]'' || 1818 || [[Northumberland]] (England), and the environs of [[Loch Lomond]] (Scotland) || 1715\u201316\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 2nd series:\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Heart of Midlothian]]'' || 1818 || [[Edinburgh]] and [[Richmond, London]] || 1736\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 3rd series:\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Bride of Lammermoor]]'' || 1819 || [[East Lothian]] (Scotland) || 1709\u201311\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[A Legend of Montrose]]'' || 1819 || [[Scottish Highlands]] || 1644-5\n|-\n|''[[Ivanhoe]]'' || 1819 || [[Yorkshire]], [[Nottinghamshire]] and [[Leicestershire]] (England)|| 1194\n|-\n|''[[The Monastery]]'' || 1820 || [[Scottish Borders]] || 1547\u201357\n|-\n|''[[The Abbot]]'' || 1820 || Various in Scotland || 1567-8\n|-\n|''[[Kenilworth (novel)|Kenilworth]]'' || 1821 || [[Berkshire]] and [[Warwickshire]] (England) || 1575\n|-\n|''[[The Pirate (novel)|The Pirate]]'' || 1822 || [[Shetland]] and [[Orkney]] || 1690s\n|-\n|''[[The Fortunes of Nigel]]'' || 1822 || [[London]] and [[Greenwich]] (England)|| 1616\u201318\n|-\n|''[[Peveril of the Peak]]'' || 1822 || [[Derbyshire]], the [[Isle of Man]], and [[London]] || 1658\u201380\n|-\n|''[[Quentin Durward]]'' || 1823 || [[Tours]] and [[P\u00e9ronne, Somme|P\u00e9ronne]] (France)<br>[[Li\u00e8ge]] ([[Wallonia]]/Belgium) || 1468\n|-\n|''[[St. Ronan's Well]]'' || 1824 || Southern Scotland || 19th century\n|-\n|''[[Redgauntlet]]'' || 1824 || Southern Scotland, and [[Cumberland]] (England)|| 1766\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of the Crusaders'':\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Betrothed (Scott novel)|The Betrothed]]'' || 1825 || Wales, and [[Gloucester]] (England)|| 1187\u201392\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Talisman (Scott novel)|The Talisman]]'' || 1825 || [[Syria]] || 1191\n|-\n|''[[Woodstock (novel)|Woodstock]]'', or, ''The Cavalier'' || 1826 || [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire|Woodstock]] and [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]] (England)<br>[[Brussels]], in the [[Spanish Netherlands]] || 1652\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Chronicles of the Canongate'', 2nd series:<ref>The first series of ''Chronicles of the Canongate'' contained two short stories ('The Highland Widow' and 'The Two Drovers'), and a short novel ''The Surgeon's Daughter'', set in the second half of the 18th century, partly in India.</ref>\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''St Valentine's Day'', or, ''[[The Fair Maid of Perth]]'' || 1828 || [[Perthshire]] (Scotland) || 1396\n|-\n|''[[Anne of Geierstein]]'', or, ''The Maiden in the Mist'' || 1829 || Switzerland and Eastern France || 1474\u201377\n|-\n|colspan=4|''Tales of my Landlord'', 4th series:<ref>A further novel, ''The Siege of Malta'', set in the Mediterranean in 1565, and an incomplete novella ''Bizarro'', set in Calabria in the first two decades of the 19th century, were first published in 2008.</ref>\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Count Robert of Paris]]'' || 1831 || [[Constantinople]] and [[\u00dcsk\u00fcdar|Scutari]] (now in [[Turkey]]) || 1097\n|-\n|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Castle Dangerous]]'' || 1831 || [[Lanarkshire]] (Scotland) || 1307\n\n|}\n\n==Chronological order, by setting==\n*1097: ''Count Robert of Paris''\n*1187\u201394: ''The Betrothed, The Talisman, Ivanhoe'' (3)\n*1307: ''Castle Dangerous''\n*1396: ''The Fair Maid of Perth''\n*1468\u201377: ''Quentin Durward, Anne of Geierstein'' (2)\n*1547\u201375: ''The Monastery, The Abbot, Kenilworth, The Siege of Malta'' (4)\n*1616\u201318: ''The Fortunes of Nigel''\n*1644\u201389: ''A Legend of Montrose, Woodstock, Peveril of the Peak, The Tale of Old Mortality, The Pirate'' (5)\n*1700\u201399: ''The Black Dwarf, The Bride of Lammermoor, Rob Roy, Heart of Midlothian, Waverley, Guy Mannering, Redgauntlet, The Antiquary'' (8)\n*19th century: ''St. Ronan's Well''\n\n==Editions==\nThe novels were all originally printed by [[James Ballantyne]] on [[the Canongate]] in Edinburgh. James Ballantyne was the brother of one of Scott's close friends, [[John Ballantyne (publisher)|John Ballantyne]] (\"Printed by James Ballantyne and Co. for Archibald Constable and Co., Edinburgh\"). \n\nThere are two definitive editions. One is the \"Magnum Opus\", a 48-volume set published between 1829 and 1833 by [[Robert Cadell]], based on previous editions, with new introductions and notes by Scott. This was the basis of almost all subsequent editions until the appearance of the standard modern edition, the [[Edinburgh edition of the waverley novels|Edinburgh Edition of the Waverley Novels]], a 30-volume set, based on early-edition texts emended mainly from the surviving manuscripts, published by Edinburgh University Press between 1993 and 2012.\n\n==Placenames==\n[[File:Edinburgh-scottm.600px.jpg|right|thumb|View from the [[Scott Monument]] of the [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Waverley Station]] roof, in [[Edinburgh]], with [[Arthur's Seat]] in the background]]\n\nIn Scotland, [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Waverley Station]] and [[Waverley Bridge]] in [[Edinburgh]] were named after these novels.\n\nIn North America, the towns of [[Waverly, Colorado]]; [[Waverly, Nebraska]]; [[Waverly, Illinois]]; [[Waverly, South Dakota]]; [[Waverly, Tioga County, New York|Waverley, New York]]; [[Waverley, Nova Scotia]]; [[Waverly, Ohio]]; [[Waverly Hall, Georgia]];<ref name=\"http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/counties-cities-neighborhoods/harris-county\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/counties-cities-neighborhoods/harris-county |title=Harris County |work=Harris County }}</ref> [[Waverly, Tennessee]],<ref name=\"waverly.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.waverly.net/hcchamber/history.htm |title=History of Humphreys County Tennessee |work=Humphreys County Chamber of Commerce |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516154432/http://www.waverly.net/hcchamber/history.htm |archivedate=May 16, 2007}}</ref>, and [[Waverly, Iowa]], take their names from these novels, as does Waverley School in Louisville, Kentucky, which later became the [[Waverly Hills Sanatorium]].\n\nThe unincorporated community of [[Ellerslie, Georgia]] is believed to be named for a character in the novels, Captain Ellerslie. <ref>http://www.kenkrakow.com/gpn/e.pdf</ref>\n\nIn Australia, the Melbourne suburbs of [[Glen Waverley, Victoria|Glen Waverley]] and [[Mount Waverley, Victoria|Mount Waverley]] and also [[Ivanhoe, Victoria| Ivanhoe]], were named after the novels as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rampantscotland.com/placenames/placename_melbourne.htm |title=Scottish Place Names in Melbourne, Australia |accessdate=23 June 2018 |last=Kendall |first=Ian |date=January 2011 |orig-year=June 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn New Zealand there is a suburb in Dunedin and a North Island town in the province of Taranaki called Waverley.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* ''[[Tales of my Landlord]]''\n* ''[[Tales of the Crusaders]]''\n* ''[[Chronicles of the Canongate]]''\n\n==Notes and references==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* A typically enthusiastic [http://www.oldandsold.com/articles28/books-4.shtml essay] on the Waverley Novels, published in 1912\n\n{{Walter Scott}}\n\n[[Category:Walter Scott novel series]]\n", "name_user": "Geierstein41", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEditions:minor change to activate cross-reference.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waverley_Novels"}
{"title_page": "Cerrej\u00f3n Formation", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Cerrej\u00f3n Formation\n| image          = Cerrejonmine3.png\n| caption        = Section of the [[Cerrej\u00f3n]] coal mine\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| period         = Paleocene\n| age            = [[Paleocene|Mid-Late Paleocene]]<br />~{{fossil range|60|58}}\n| prilithology   = [[Coal]], [[mudstone]], [[siltstone]]\n| otherlithology = [[Sandstone]]\n| region         = [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]], [[Cesar Department|Cesar]]\n| country        = {{flag|Colombia}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|11|05|22|N|72|40|31|W|display=inline,title}}\n| unitof         = [[Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin]]\n| subunits       = Lower, middle, upper\n| underlies      = [[Tabaco Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Manantial Formation]]\n| thickness      = Up to {{convert|750|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            = \n| map_caption    =\n| namedfor       = [[Cerrej\u00f3n]]\n| namedby        = [[Thomas van der Hammen|Hammen]]\n| year_ts        = 1958\n| location_ts    = [[Cerrej\u00f3n]]\n| coordinates_ts = {{coord|11|05|22|N|72|40|31|W|display:inline}}\n| paleocoordinates_ts = {{coord|8.5|N|59.2|W|display:inline}}<ref name=PaleoDBLaPuentePit>[https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicCollectionSearch?collection_no=106271 La Puente Pit] in the [[Paleobiology Database]]</ref>\n| region_ts      = [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]]\n| country_ts     = {{COL}}\n| thickness_ts   = \n}}\nThe '''Cerrej\u00f3n Formation''' is a geologic formation in [[Colombia]] dating back to the Middle-Late [[Paleocene]]. It is found in the El Cerrej\u00f3n sub-basin of the [[Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin]] of [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]] and [[Cesar Department|Cesar]]. The formation consists of [[bituminous coal]] fields that are an important economic resource. Coal from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is mined extensively from the [[Cerrej\u00f3n]] [[open-pit mining|open-pit]] coal mine, one of the largest in the world. The formation also bears fossils that are the earliest record of [[Neotropical]] [[rainforest]]s.<ref name=Wetal09>Wing et al., 2009</ref>\n\n== Definition ==\nThe formation was first named Septarias Formation and in 1958 renamed to Cerrej\u00f3n Formation by [[Thomas van der Hammen]], probably based on an earlier report by Notestein.<ref name=Rodriguez_p163>Rodr\u00edguez & Londo\u00f1o, 2002, p.163</ref>\n\n== Geology ==\n{{main|Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin}}\nThe Cerrej\u00f3n Formation, with an assigned total thickness of {{convert|750|m|ft}},<ref name=Rodriguez_p163/> is subdivided into lower, middle, and upper groups based on the thickness and distribution of coal beds. On average the coal beds are {{convert|3|m|ft}} thick, and range from {{convert|0.7|m|ft}} to {{convert|10|m|ft}} in thickness. The thickest beds are in the upper part of the formation.<ref name=TFTS06>{{cite book |last=Tewalt |first=S. J. |author2=Finkelman, R. B. |author3=Torres, I. E. |author4= Simoni, F.  |year=2006 |chapter=World Coal Quality Inventory: Colombia |title=World Coal Quality Inventory: South America |editor=Alex W. Karlsen |editor2=Susan J. Tewalt |editor3=Linda J. Bragg |editor4=Robert B. Finkelman |series=U.S. Geological Survey Open File Report 2006 |issue=1241 |publisher=United States Geological Survey |pages=132\u2013157 | chapter-url = http://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2006/1241/}}</ref> The Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is laterally equivalent with the [[Los Cuervos Formation|Los Cuervos]] and [[Bogot\u00e1 Formation]]s to the south; [[Orinoqu\u00eda Region|Llanos Orientales]] and [[Altiplano Cundiboyacense]] respectively. The formation is also time-equivalent with the [[Marcelina Formation]] of the Venezuelan [[Serran\u00eda del Perij\u00e1]] and the [[Catatumbo Formation]] of the southwestern Colombian part of the [[Maracaibo Basin]], the [[Catatumbo Basin]].<ref name=Ojeda_p69>Ojeda & S\u00e1nchez, 2013, p.69</ref> The formation has also been described as laterally equivalent to the [[Mostrencos Formation|Mostrencos]] and [[Santa Cruz Formation, Venezuela|Santa Cruz Formation]]s of Venezuela.<ref name=Rodriguez_p165>Rodr\u00edguez & Londo\u00f1o, 2002, p.165</ref>\n\nBased on [[Facies|lithofacies]] associations and [[Paleobotany|paleofloral]] composition, the [[depositional environment]] fluctuated from an [[estuarine]]-influenced [[coastal plain]] at the base of the formation to a [[fluvial]]-influenced coastal plain at the top.<ref name=Jetal07>{{cite journal |last=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first=C.A. |author2=Pardo Trujillo, A. |author3=Rueda, M. |author4=Torres, V. |author5=Harrington, G.J. |author6= Mora, G. |year=2007 |title=The palynology of the Cerrejon Formation (upper Paleocene) of northern Colombia |journal=Palynology |volume=31 |pages=153\u2013189 |doi=10.2113/gspalynol.31.1.153}}</ref>\n\nIn the geologically recent past, some coal in the formation has spontaneously and naturally combusted to form clinker, red and brick-looking burnt coal. These rocks outcrop irregularly and are up to {{convert|100|m|ft}} thick. Clinker is found near deformed zones such as [[fault (geology)|fault]]s or tight folds, and is older than the deformities themselves. They are thought to have combusted after the development of the  Cerrej\u00f3n [[thrust fault]] and [[alluvial fan]].<ref name=Qetal09>{{cite journal |last=Quintero |first=J. A. |author2=Candela, S. A. |author3=Rios, C. A. |author4=Montes, C. |author5=Uribe, C. |year=2009 |title=Spontaneous combustion of the Upper Paleocene Cerrej\u00f3n Formation coal and generation of clinker in La Guajira Peninsula (Caribbean Region of Colombia) |journal=International Journal of Coal Geology | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | location = Amsterdam |volume=80 |issue=3 |pages=196\u2013210 |doi=10.1016/j.coal.2009.09.004 | issn = 0166-5162}}</ref>\n\n== Paleoenvironment ==\n[[File:Titanoboa NT.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Reconstruction of ''[[Titanoboa|Titanoboa cerrejonensis]]'']]\n[[Fossil]]s found from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation are the earliest record of Neotropical rainforests, with an abundance of plant macrofossils and [[palynomorph]]s. The Cerrej\u00f3n Formation also records a riverine vertebrate fauna that includes [[lungfish]], turtles, snakes, and [[crocodyliform]]s. Based on these fossils and the stratigraphy of the formation, the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation was likely formed on a coastal plain, covered in a wet tropical rainforest and incised by a large river system.<ref name=Hetal09>Head et al., 2009</ref>\n\nThe rainforest is estimated to have been around 5\u00b0N [[paleolatitude]].<ref name=Wetal09/> During the Paleocene, equatorial temperatures were much higher than they are today. Based on the size of the giant [[boid]] ''[[Titanoboa]]'', specimens of which have been found in the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation, the mean annual temperature of Paleocene equatorial South America was between {{convert|30|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} and {{convert|34|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}. This is the minimum annual temperature range that a  [[poikilotherm]] as large as ''Titanoboa'' could live.<ref name=Hetal09/> It is consistent with Paleocene climate models which predict greenhouse temperatures and an atmospheric [[Carbon dioxide|pCO<sub>2</sub>]] concentration of around 2,000 parts per million.<ref name=SSM03>{{cite journal |last=Shellito |first=C. J. |author2=Sloan, L. C. |author3= Huber, M.  |year=2003 |title=Climate model sensitivity to atmospheric CO2 levels in the Early\u2013Middle Paleogene |journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology |volume=193 |issue=1 |pages=113\u2013123 | doi = 10.1016/S0031-0182(02)00718-6|bibcode=2003PPP...193..113S }}</ref> Paleotemperature estimates based on fossil leaf assemblages from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation predict the mean annual temperature to be {{convert|6|to|8|C|F}} lower than other estimates.<ref name=HJW05>{{cite book |last=Herrera |first=F. |author2=Jaramillo, C. |author3= Wing, S. L.  |year=2005 |chapter=Warm (not hot) tropics during the Late Paleocene: First continental evidence |title=Proceedings of American Geophysical Union Fall Meeting, San Francisco, California, USA |volume=86 |publisher=American Geophysical Union |location=Washington, D.C. USA |pages=51C\u20130608 | bibcode = 2005AGUFMPP51C0608H}}</ref> However, such temperature estimates based on [[riparian]] and [[wetland]] rainforest paleoflora have been considered underestimates.<ref name=KD03>{{cite journal |last=Kowalski |first=E. A. |author2=Dilcher, D. L. |year=2003 |title=Warmer paleotemperatures for terrestrial ecosystems |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=100 |issue=1 |pages=167\u2013170 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.232693599 |bibcode = 2002PNAS..100..167K |pmid=12493844 |pmc=140915}}</ref>\n\nMean annual temperatures of {{convert|30|to|34|C|F}} are considered to be too high for modern tropical forests,<ref name=BJ04>{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=R. J. |author2=Johnson, K. R. |year=2004 |title=South American palaeobotany and the origins of neotropical rainforests |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B |volume=359 |pages=1595\u20131610 | doi = 10.1098/rstb.2004.1531 |pmid=15519975 |pmc=1693437 |issue=1450}}</ref> but the Cerrej\u00f3n rainforest could have been maintained by increased atmospheric pCO<sub>2</sub> levels and the high regional rainfall, which is estimated to have been around {{convert|4|m|ft}} per year.<ref name=Jetal07/><ref name=Hetal09/><ref name=HSZ91>{{cite journal |last=Hogan |first=K. P. |author2=Smith, A. P. |author3= Ziska, L. H.  |year=1991 |title=Potential effects of elevated CO<sub>2</sub> and changes in temperature on tropical plants |journal=Plant, Cell & Environment |volume=14 |issue=8 |pages=763\u2013778|doi = 10.1111/j.1365-3040.1991.tb01441.x }}</ref>\n\n=== Flora ===\n{{see also|Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin#Fossil content}}\n[[File:Canna jaegeriana (14490676206).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Fossil [[Zingiberales]] have been uncovered from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation]]\nThe floral record of the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is well known, with many identifiable and well preserved plant microfossils having been found from the Cerrej\u00f3n mine. The fossils are well preserved, and in some cases their cell structure is intact.<ref name=FMNH>{{cite news |title=Plant fossils give first real picture of earliest Neotropical rainforests |last=Kanapaux |first=B. |newspaper=Science Stories: Florida Museum of Natural History |date=October 2009 |url=http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/sciencestories/2009/neotropical_rainforest.htm |accessdate=14 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604132301/http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/sciencestories/2009/neotropical_rainforest.htm |archive-date=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In comparison to modern Neotropical rainforests, the diversity of plants is quite low. This may be an indication of the early stage of Neotropical diversification, or a delayed recovery period following the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event]].<ref name=Wetal09/>\n\nMany plants from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation belong to [[Family (biology)|families]] that are still common today in modern Neotropical rainforests. There is a diverse variety of [[Arecaceae|palms]] and [[legume]]s in the formation. In addition to palms and legumes, much of the biomass of the Paleocene forest consisted of [[laurales]], [[malvales]], [[Menispermaceae|menisperms]], [[Araceae|aroids]], and [[Zingiberales|zingiberaleans]].<ref name=Wetal09/> Studies of fossil plants from [[Cretaceous]]-age sites indicate that the floral composition below the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene boundary]] (K\u2013T boundary) was very different from that of the Paleocene. Legumes are absent from Cretaceous strata, and likely appeared or diversified during the Paleocene.<ref name=FMNH/>\n\nThe presence of these types of flora in Paleocene strata shows that plants characteristic of modern Neotropical rainforests have existed for geologically long periods of time, being able to withstand climatic and geographic changes in South America. It has been suggested that today's Neotropical rainforests are the result of environmental changes brought about by [[Quaternary glaciation|Quaternary glacial cycles]] (i.e. the recent ice age). These cycles would have caused fluctuation in the diversity and extent of rainforests. If this was the case, the current diversity of the [[Amazon rainforest]] would be a recent speciation in a changing environment.<ref name=RPPH01>{{cite journal |last=Richardson |first=J. E. |author2=Pennington, R. T. |author3=Pennington, T. D. |author4= Hollingsworth, P. M.  |year=2001 |title=Rapid diversification of a species-rich genus of Neotropical rain forest trees |journal=Science |pmid=11567135 |volume=293 |issue=5538 |pages=2242\u20132245 |doi=10.1126/science.1061421|bibcode = 2001Sci...293.2242R }}</ref> However, the floral record from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation shows that the current diversity of the Amazon Rainforest can be traced back into the early Cenozoic.<ref name=Wetal09/>\n\n=== Fauna ===\n[[File:Carbonemys Cofrinii.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Reconstruction of the giant ''[[Carbonemys|Carbonemys cofrinii]]'']]\nFeeding damage from insects is evident on some of the plant macrofossils from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation. One survey of plant macrofossils showed that around half of the studied specimens had been attacked by herbivorous insects.<ref name=Wetal09/> The insects that damaged the leaves were predominantly [[Generalist and specialist species|generalist]] feeders, unlike modern Neotropical insects that are mainly [[Generalist and specialist species|specialist]] herbivores. There is no evidence of the elevated insect-feeding diversity or [[Host (biology)|host]]-specialized feeding associations that are seen in later [[Neotropical]] forests. The insect diversity in the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is low in comparison to the diversity of insects in Neotropical rainforests today, and it is likely that leaf damage was made by relatively few species.<ref name=Wetal09/>\n\nRemains of the giant [[Boidae|boid]] ''[[Titanoboa|Titanoboa cerrejonensis]]'' have been found from a gray [[claystone]] layer underlying Coal Seam 90 in the Cerrej\u00f3n mine. ''Titanoboa'' is the [[Largest prehistoric animals#Reptiles .28Reptilia.29|largest known snake]] to have ever existed, reaching an estimated length of {{convert|12.8|m|ft}}. ''Eunectes'', the [[anaconda]], is likely to be a close living analogue of ''Titanoboa''.<ref name=Hetal09/>\n\nA [[dyrosaurid]] [[crocodylomorph]] called ''[[Cerrejonisuchus|Cerrejonisuchus improcerus]]'' was described in 2010 from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation in the same layer as ''Titanoboa''. It was a small dyrosaurid, and had the shortest snout length relative to its skull length of any dyrosaurid. Most dyrosaurids were marine, with long snouts adapted for catching fish. The short snout of ''Cerrejonisuchus'' is likely to have been an adaptation for a more generalized diet in a transitional aquatic environment.<ref name=HBCJ10>{{cite journal |last=Hastings |first=A. K |author2=Bloch, J. I. |author3=Cadena, E. A. |author4= Jaramillo, C. A.  |year=2010 |title=A new small short-snouted dyrosaurid (Crocodylomorpha, Mesoeucrocodylia) from the Paleocene of northeastern Colombia |journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=139\u2013162 |doi=10.1080/02724630903409204}}</ref> It is possible that ''Cerrejonisuchus'' was a food source for ''Titanoboa'', as the two inhabited the same riverine environment.<ref name=UFnews>{{cite news|title=UF researchers: Ancient crocodile relative likely food source for Titanoboa |last=Kanapaux |first=B. |newspaper=University of Florida News |date=2 February 2010 |url=http://news.ufl.edu/2010/02/02/titanoboa-food/ |accessdate=3 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608080906/http://news.ufl.edu/2010/02/02/titanoboa-food/ |archivedate=8 June 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> The anaconda has been documented consuming [[caiman]]s, a feeding habit that is similar to the inferred habit of ''Titanoboa''. A second dyrosaurid, ''[[Acherontisuchus]]'', was named in 2011 from the formation. With a large body and long snout, it resembles most other dyrosaurids.<ref name=HBJ11>Hastings et al., 2011</ref>\n\n== Coal resources ==\n[[File:Cerrejonmine2.png|thumb|right|250px|Coal mining in the Cerrej\u00f3n open-pit mine]]\n{{main|Cerrej\u00f3n mine}}\nThe Cerrej\u00f3n Formation contains extensive coal seams that are mined primarily at the Cerrej\u00f3n mine. The coal is desirable for its low [[Coal ash|ash]] and [[sulfur]] content and for its resistance to caking. Cerrej\u00f3n is Colombia's largest coal producing mine, with most of the production exported to Europe. It is the largest coal mining operation in Latin America, with an estimated 28.4 million tons mined in 2006.<ref name=TFTS06/><ref name=M-T>{{cite web |url=http://www.mining-technology.com/projects/cerrejon/ |title=El Cerrej\u00f3n Coal Mine, Colombia |work=Mining-technology.com |publisher=Net Resources International |accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n{{clearboth}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite LSA |last=Hastings |first=Alexander K. |last2=Bloch |first2=Jonathan I. |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |year=2011 |title=A new longirostrine Dyrosaurid (Crocodylomorpha, Mesoeucrocodylia) from the Paleocene of north-eastern Colombia: Biogeographocal and behavioural implications for New-World Dyrosayridae |url=http://www.stri.si.edu/sites/publications/PDFs/STRI-W_Jaramillo_2011_Hasting_croc_Cerrejon.pdf |journal=[[Palaeontology (journal)|Palaeontology]] |volume=54 |pages=1095\u20131116 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Head |first=J.J. |last2=Bloch |first2=J.I. |last3=Hastings |first3=A.K. |last4=Bourque |first4=J.R. |last5=[[Edwin Cadena|Cadena]] |first5=E.A. |last6=Herrera |first6=F.A. |last7=Polly |first7=P.D. |last8=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first8=C.A. |year=2009 |title=Giant boid snake from the paleocene neotropics reveals hotter past equatorial temperatures |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v457/n7230/abs/nature07671.html |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=457 |pages=715\u2013718 |accessdate=2017-06-14|bibcode=2009Natur.457..715H |doi=10.1038/nature07671 }}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Ojeda Marulanda |first=Carolina |last2=S\u00e1nchez Qui\u00f1\u00f3nez |first2=Carlos Alberto |year=2013 |title=Petrograf\u00eda, petrolog\u00eda y an\u00e1lisis de procedencia de unidades pale\u00f3genas en las cuencas Cesar - Rancher\u00eda y Catatumbo |url=http://www.scielo.org.co/pdf/boge/v35n1/v35n1a06.pdf |journal=Bolet\u00edn de Geolog\u00eda, [[Industrial University of Santander|Universidad Industrial de Santander]] |volume=35 |pages=67\u201380 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Rodr\u00edguez |first=Gabriel |last2=Londo\u00f1o |first2=Ana Cristina |year=2002 |title=Mapa geol\u00f3gico del Departamento de La Guajira - 1:250,000 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/270882602_MAPA_GEOLOGICO_DEL_DEPARTAMENTO_DE_LA_GUAJIRA |publisher=[[INGEOMINAS]] |pages=1\u2013259 |accessdate=2017-08-08}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Wing |first=Scott L. |last2=Herrera |first2=Fabiany |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |last4=G\u00f3mez Navarro |first4=Carolina |last5=Wilf |first5=Peter |last6=Labandeira |first6=Conrad C. |year=2009 |title=Late Paleocene fossils from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation, Columbia ((sic)), are the earliest record of Neotropical rainforest |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/106/44/18627.abstract |journal=Proceedings of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] |volume=106 |pages=18627\u201318632 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite LSA |last=[[Edwin Cadena|Cadena]] |first=Edwin A. |last2=Ksepka |first2=Daniel T. |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |last4=Bloch |first4=Jonathan I. |year=2012a |title=New pelomedusoid turtles from the late Palaeocene Cerrej\u00f3n Formation of Colombia and their implications for phylogeny and body size evolution |url=http://www.stri.si.edu/sites/publications/PDFs/STRI-W_Jaramillo_2012_Cadena_carbonemys_cerrejon.pdf |journal=[[Journal of Systematic Palaeontology]] |volume=10 |pages=313\u2013331 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=[[Edwin Cadena|Cadena]] |first=Edwin A. |last2=Bloch |first2=Jonathan I. |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |year=2012b |title=New bothremydid turtle (Testudines, Pleurodira) from the Paleocene of northeastern Colombia |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-paleontology/article/new-bothremydid-turtle-testudines-pleurodira-from-the-paleocene-of-northeastern-colombia/7648D30CCCD6BC3A50515E4B7AF31603 |journal=[[Journal of Paleontology]] |volume=86 |pages=688\u2013698 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=[[Edwin Cadena|Cadena]] |first=Edwin A. |last2=Bloch |first2=Jonathan I. |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |year=2010 |title=New Podocnemidid Turtle (Testudines: Pleurodira) from the Middle-Upper Paleocene of South America |url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1080/02724631003621946 |journal=[[Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology]] |volume=30 |pages=367\u2013382 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Hastings |first=Alexander K. |last2=Bloch |first2=Jonathan I. |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |year=2014 |title=A new blunt-snouted dyrosaurid, Anthracosuchus balrogus gen. et sp. nov. (Crocodylomorpha, Mesoeucrocodylia), from the Palaeocene of Colombia |url=http://www.stri.si.edu/sites/publications/PDFs/Hasting_2014_anthracosuchus_Cerrejon.pdf |journal=[[Historical Biology]] |volume=27 |pages=998\u20131020 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Herrera |first=Fabiany A. |last2=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first2=Carlos A. |last3=Dilcher |first3=David L. |last4=Wing |first4=Scott L. |last5=G\u00f3mez N |first5=Carolina |year=2008 |title=Fossil Araceae from a Paleocene neotropical rainforest in Colombia |url=http://www.amjbot.org/content/95/12/1569 |journal=[[American Journal of Botany]] |volume=95 |pages=1569\u20131583 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n\n{{Paleontology in Colombia|state=expanded}}\n{{Portal bar|Geology|Paleontology|Colombia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cerrejon Formation}}\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Cerrej\u00f3n Formation| ]]\n[[Category:Cesar\u2013Rancher\u00eda Basin|Formations]]\n[[Category:Paleogene Colombia]]\n[[Category:Paleocene Series of South America]]\n[[Category:Itaboraian]]\n[[Category:Peligran]]\n[[Category:Thanetian Stage]]\n[[Category:Coal in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Coal formations]]\n[[Category:Mudstone formations]]\n[[Category:Sandstone formations]]\n[[Category:Siltstone formations]]\n[[Category:Fluvial deposits]]\n[[Category:Reservoir rock formations]]\n[[Category:Source rock formations]]\n[[Category:Geography of Cesar Department|Formations]]\n[[Category:Geography of La Guajira Department|Formations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Cerrej\u00f3n Formation\n| image          = Cerrejonmine3.png\n| caption        = Section of the [[Cerrej\u00f3n]] coal mine\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| period         = Paleocene\n| age            = [[Paleocene|Mid-Late Paleocene]]<br />~{{fossil range|60|58}}\n| prilithology   = [[Coal]], [[mudstone]], [[siltstone]]\n| otherlithology = [[Sandstone]]\n| region         = [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]], [[Cesar Department|Cesar]]\n| country        = {{flag|Colombia}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|11|05|22|N|72|40|31|W|display=inline,title}}\n| unitof         = [[Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin]]\n| subunits       = Lower, middle, upper\n| underlies      = [[Tabaco Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Manantial Formation]]\n| thickness      = Up to {{convert|750|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            = \n| map_caption    =\n| namedfor       = [[Cerrej\u00f3n]]\n| namedby        = [[Thomas van der Hammen|Hammen]]\n| year_ts        = 1958\n| location_ts    = [[Cerrej\u00f3n]]\n| coordinates_ts = {{coord|11|05|22|N|72|40|31|W|display:inline}}\n| paleocoordinates_ts = {{coord|8.5|N|59.2|W|display:inline}}<ref name=PaleoDBLaPuentePit>[https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicCollectionSearch?collection_no=106271 La Puente Pit] in the [[Paleobiology Database]]</ref>\n| region_ts      = [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]]\n| country_ts     = {{COL}}\n| thickness_ts   = \n}}\nThe '''Cerrej\u00f3n Formation''' is a geologic formation in [[Colombia]] dating back to the Middle-Late [[Paleocene]]. It is found in the El Cerrej\u00f3n sub-basin of the [[Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin]] of [[La Guajira Department|La Guajira]] and [[Cesar Department|Cesar]]. The formation consists of [[bituminous coal]] fields that are an important economic resource. Coal from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is mined extensively from the [[Cerrej\u00f3n]] [[open-pit mining|open-pit]] coal mine, one of the largest in the world. The formation also bears fossils that are the earliest record of [[Neotropical]] [[rainforest]]s.<ref name=Wetal09>Wing et al., 2009</ref>\n\n== Definition ==\nThe formation was first named Septarias Formation and in 1958 renamed to Cerrej\u00f3n Formation by [[Thomas van der Hammen]], probably based on an earlier report by Notestein.<ref name=Rodriguez_p163>Rodr\u00edguez & Londo\u00f1o, 2002, p.163</ref>\n\n== Geology ==\n{{main|Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin}}\nThe Cerrej\u00f3n Formation, with an assigned total thickness of {{convert|750|m|ft}},<ref name=Rodriguez_p163/> is subdivided into lower, middle, and upper groups based on the thickness and distribution of coal beds. On average the coal beds are {{convert|3|m|ft}} thick, and range from {{convert|0.7|m|ft}} to {{convert|10|m|ft}} in thickness. The thickest beds are in the upper part of the formation.<ref name=TFTS06>{{cite book |last=Tewalt |first=S. J. |author2=Finkelman, R. B. |author3=Torres, I. E. |author4= Simoni, F.  |year=2006 |chapter=World Coal Quality Inventory: Colombia |title=World Coal Quality Inventory: South America |editors=Alex W. Karlsen, Susan J. Tewalt, Linda J. Bragg, and Robert B. Finkelman (eds.) |series=U.S. Geological Survey Open File Report 2006 |issue=1241 |publisher=United States Geological Survey |pages=132\u2013157 | chapter-url = http://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2006/1241/}}</ref> The Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is laterally equivalent with the [[Los Cuervos Formation|Los Cuervos]] and [[Bogot\u00e1 Formation]]s to the south; [[Orinoqu\u00eda Region|Llanos Orientales]] and [[Altiplano Cundiboyacense]] respectively. The formation is also time-equivalent with the [[Marcelina Formation]] of the Venezuelan [[Serran\u00eda del Perij\u00e1]] and the [[Catatumbo Formation]] of the southwestern Colombian part of the [[Maracaibo Basin]], the [[Catatumbo Basin]].<ref name=Ojeda_p69>Ojeda & S\u00e1nchez, 2013, p.69</ref> The formation has also been described as laterally equivalent to the [[Mostrencos Formation|Mostrencos]] and [[Santa Cruz Formation, Venezuela|Santa Cruz Formation]]s of Venezuela.<ref name=Rodriguez_p165>Rodr\u00edguez & Londo\u00f1o, 2002, p.165</ref>\n\nBased on [[Facies|lithofacies]] associations and [[Paleobotany|paleofloral]] composition, the [[depositional environment]] fluctuated from an [[estuarine]]-influenced [[coastal plain]] at the base of the formation to a [[fluvial]]-influenced coastal plain at the top.<ref name=Jetal07>{{cite journal |last=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first=C.A. |author2=Pardo Trujillo, A. |author3=Rueda, M. |author4=Torres, V. |author5=Harrington, G.J. |author6= Mora, G. |year=2007 |title=The palynology of the Cerrejon Formation (upper Paleocene) of northern Colombia |journal=Palynology |volume=31 |pages=153\u2013189 |doi=10.2113/gspalynol.31.1.153}}</ref>\n\nIn the geologically recent past, some coal in the formation has spontaneously and naturally combusted to form clinker, red and brick-looking burnt coal. These rocks outcrop irregularly and are up to {{convert|100|m|ft}} thick. Clinker is found near deformed zones such as [[fault (geology)|fault]]s or tight folds, and is older than the deformities themselves. They are thought to have combusted after the development of the  Cerrej\u00f3n [[thrust fault]] and [[alluvial fan]].<ref name=Qetal09>{{cite journal |last=Quintero |first=J. A. |author2=Candela, S. A. |author3=Rios, C. A. |author4=Montes, C. |author5=Uribe, C. |year=2009 |title=Spontaneous combustion of the Upper Paleocene Cerrej\u00f3n Formation coal and generation of clinker in La Guajira Peninsula (Caribbean Region of Colombia) |journal=International Journal of Coal Geology | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | location = Amsterdam |volume=80 |issue=3 |pages=196\u2013210 |doi=10.1016/j.coal.2009.09.004 | issn = 0166-5162}}</ref>\n\n== Paleoenvironment ==\n[[File:Titanoboa NT.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Reconstruction of ''[[Titanoboa|Titanoboa cerrejonensis]]'']]\n[[Fossil]]s found from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation are the earliest record of Neotropical rainforests, with an abundance of plant macrofossils and [[palynomorph]]s. The Cerrej\u00f3n Formation also records a riverine vertebrate fauna that includes [[lungfish]], turtles, snakes, and [[crocodyliform]]s. Based on these fossils and the stratigraphy of the formation, the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation was likely formed on a coastal plain, covered in a wet tropical rainforest and incised by a large river system.<ref name=Hetal09>Head et al., 2009</ref>\n\nThe rainforest is estimated to have been around 5\u00b0N [[paleolatitude]].<ref name=Wetal09/> During the Paleocene, equatorial temperatures were much higher than they are today. Based on the size of the giant [[boid]] ''[[Titanoboa]]'', specimens of which have been found in the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation, the mean annual temperature of Paleocene equatorial South America was between {{convert|30|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} and {{convert|34|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}. This is the minimum annual temperature range that a  [[poikilotherm]] as large as ''Titanoboa'' could live.<ref name=Hetal09/> It is consistent with Paleocene climate models which predict greenhouse temperatures and an atmospheric [[Carbon dioxide|pCO<sub>2</sub>]] concentration of around 2,000 parts per million.<ref name=SSM03>{{cite journal |last=Shellito |first=C. J. |author2=Sloan, L. C. |author3= Huber, M.  |year=2003 |title=Climate model sensitivity to atmospheric CO2 levels in the Early\u2013Middle Paleogene |journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology |volume=193 |issue=1 |pages=113\u2013123 | doi = 10.1016/S0031-0182(02)00718-6|bibcode=2003PPP...193..113S }}</ref> Paleotemperature estimates based on fossil leaf assemblages from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation predict the mean annual temperature to be {{convert|6|to|8|C|F}} lower than other estimates.<ref name=HJW05>{{cite book |last=Herrera |first=F. |author2=Jaramillo, C. |author3= Wing, S. L.  |year=2005 |chapter=Warm (not hot) tropics during the Late Paleocene: First continental evidence |title=Proceedings of American Geophysical Union Fall Meeting, San Francisco, California, USA |volume=86 |publisher=American Geophysical Union |location=Washington, D.C. USA |pages=51C\u20130608 | bibcode = 2005AGUFMPP51C0608H}}</ref> However, such temperature estimates based on [[riparian]] and [[wetland]] rainforest paleoflora have been considered underestimates.<ref name=KD03>{{cite journal |last=Kowalski |first=E. A. |author2=Dilcher, D. L. |year=2003 |title=Warmer paleotemperatures for terrestrial ecosystems |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=100 |issue=1 |pages=167\u2013170 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.232693599 |bibcode = 2002PNAS..100..167K |pmid=12493844 |pmc=140915}}</ref>\n\nMean annual temperatures of {{convert|30|to|34|C|F}} are considered to be too high for modern tropical forests,<ref name=BJ04>{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=R. J. |author2=Johnson, K. R. |year=2004 |title=South American palaeobotany and the origins of neotropical rainforests |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B |volume=359 |pages=1595\u20131610 | doi = 10.1098/rstb.2004.1531 |pmid=15519975 |pmc=1693437 |issue=1450}}</ref> but the Cerrej\u00f3n rainforest could have been maintained by increased atmospheric pCO<sub>2</sub> levels and the high regional rainfall, which is estimated to have been around {{convert|4|m|ft}} per year.<ref name=Jetal07/><ref name=Hetal09/><ref name=HSZ91>{{cite journal |last=Hogan |first=K. P. |author2=Smith, A. P. |author3= Ziska, L. H.  |year=1991 |title=Potential effects of elevated CO<sub>2</sub> and changes in temperature on tropical plants |journal=Plant, Cell & Environment |volume=14 |issue=8 |pages=763\u2013778|doi = 10.1111/j.1365-3040.1991.tb01441.x }}</ref>\n\n=== Flora ===\n{{see also|Cesar-Rancher\u00eda Basin#Fossil content}}\n[[File:Canna jaegeriana (14490676206).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Fossil [[Zingiberales]] have been uncovered from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation]]\nThe floral record of the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is well known, with many identifiable and well preserved plant microfossils having been found from the Cerrej\u00f3n mine. The fossils are well preserved, and in some cases their cell structure is intact.<ref name=FMNH>{{cite news |title=Plant fossils give first real picture of earliest Neotropical rainforests |last=Kanapaux |first=B. |newspaper=Science Stories: Florida Museum of Natural History |date=October 2009 |url=http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/sciencestories/2009/neotropical_rainforest.htm |accessdate=14 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604132301/http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/sciencestories/2009/neotropical_rainforest.htm |archive-date=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In comparison to modern Neotropical rainforests, the diversity of plants is quite low. This may be an indication of the early stage of Neotropical diversification, or a delayed recovery period following the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event]].<ref name=Wetal09/>\n\nMany plants from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation belong to [[Family (biology)|families]] that are still common today in modern Neotropical rainforests. There is a diverse variety of [[Arecaceae|palms]] and [[legume]]s in the formation. In addition to palms and legumes, much of the biomass of the Paleocene forest consisted of [[laurales]], [[malvales]], [[Menispermaceae|menisperms]], [[Araceae|aroids]], and [[Zingiberales|zingiberaleans]].<ref name=Wetal09/> Studies of fossil plants from [[Cretaceous]]-age sites indicate that the floral composition below the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene boundary]] (K\u2013T boundary) was very different from that of the Paleocene. Legumes are absent from Cretaceous strata, and likely appeared or diversified during the Paleocene.<ref name=FMNH/>\n\nThe presence of these types of flora in Paleocene strata shows that plants characteristic of modern Neotropical rainforests have existed for geologically long periods of time, being able to withstand climatic and geographic changes in South America. It has been suggested that today's Neotropical rainforests are the result of environmental changes brought about by [[Quaternary glaciation|Quaternary glacial cycles]] (i.e. the recent ice age). These cycles would have caused fluctuation in the diversity and extent of rainforests. If this was the case, the current diversity of the [[Amazon rainforest]] would be a recent speciation in a changing environment.<ref name=RPPH01>{{cite journal |last=Richardson |first=J. E. |author2=Pennington, R. T. |author3=Pennington, T. D. |author4= Hollingsworth, P. M.  |year=2001 |title=Rapid diversification of a species-rich genus of Neotropical rain forest trees |journal=Science |pmid=11567135 |volume=293 |issue=5538 |pages=2242\u20132245 |doi=10.1126/science.1061421|bibcode = 2001Sci...293.2242R }}</ref> However, the floral record from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation shows that the current diversity of the Amazon Rainforest can be traced back into the early Cenozoic.<ref name=Wetal09/>\n\n=== Fauna ===\n[[File:Carbonemys Cofrinii.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Reconstruction of the giant ''[[Carbonemys|Carbonemys cofrinii]]'']]\nFeeding damage from insects is evident on some of the plant macrofossils from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation. One survey of plant macrofossils showed that around half of the studied specimens had been attacked by herbivorous insects.<ref name=Wetal09/> The insects that damaged the leaves were predominantly [[Generalist and specialist species|generalist]] feeders, unlike modern Neotropical insects that are mainly [[Generalist and specialist species|specialist]] herbivores. There is no evidence of the elevated insect-feeding diversity or [[Host (biology)|host]]-specialized feeding associations that are seen in later [[Neotropical]] forests. The insect diversity in the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation is low in comparison to the diversity of insects in Neotropical rainforests today, and it is likely that leaf damage was made by relatively few species.<ref name=Wetal09/>\n\nRemains of the giant [[Boidae|boid]] ''[[Titanoboa|Titanoboa cerrejonensis]]'' have been found from a gray [[claystone]] layer underlying Coal Seam 90 in the Cerrej\u00f3n mine. ''Titanoboa'' is the [[Largest prehistoric animals#Reptiles .28Reptilia.29|largest known snake]] to have ever existed, reaching an estimated length of {{convert|12.8|m|ft}}. ''Eunectes'', the [[anaconda]], is likely to be a close living analogue of ''Titanoboa''.<ref name=Hetal09/>\n\nA [[dyrosaurid]] [[crocodylomorph]] called ''[[Cerrejonisuchus|Cerrejonisuchus improcerus]]'' was described in 2010 from the Cerrej\u00f3n Formation in the same layer as ''Titanoboa''. It was a small dyrosaurid, and had the shortest snout length relative to its skull length of any dyrosaurid. Most dyrosaurids were marine, with long snouts adapted for catching fish. The short snout of ''Cerrejonisuchus'' is likely to have been an adaptation for a more generalized diet in a transitional aquatic environment.<ref name=HBCJ10>{{cite journal |last=Hastings |first=A. K |author2=Bloch, J. I. |author3=Cadena, E. A. |author4= Jaramillo, C. A.  |year=2010 |title=A new small short-snouted dyrosaurid (Crocodylomorpha, Mesoeucrocodylia) from the Paleocene of northeastern Colombia |journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=139\u2013162 |doi=10.1080/02724630903409204}}</ref> It is possible that ''Cerrejonisuchus'' was a food source for ''Titanoboa'', as the two inhabited the same riverine environment.<ref name=UFnews>{{cite news|title=UF researchers: Ancient crocodile relative likely food source for Titanoboa |last=Kanapaux |first=B. |newspaper=University of Florida News |date=2 February 2010 |url=http://news.ufl.edu/2010/02/02/titanoboa-food/ |accessdate=3 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608080906/http://news.ufl.edu/2010/02/02/titanoboa-food/ |archivedate=8 June 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> The anaconda has been documented consuming [[caiman]]s, a feeding habit that is similar to the inferred habit of ''Titanoboa''. A second dyrosaurid, ''[[Acherontisuchus]]'', was named in 2011 from the formation. With a large body and long snout, it resembles most other dyrosaurids.<ref name=HBJ11>Hastings et al., 2011</ref>\n\n== Coal resources ==\n[[File:Cerrejonmine2.png|thumb|right|250px|Coal mining in the Cerrej\u00f3n open-pit mine]]\n{{main|Cerrej\u00f3n mine}}\nThe Cerrej\u00f3n Formation contains extensive coal seams that are mined primarily at the Cerrej\u00f3n mine. The coal is desirable for its low [[Coal ash|ash]] and [[sulfur]] content and for its resistance to caking. Cerrej\u00f3n is Colombia's largest coal producing mine, with most of the production exported to Europe. It is the largest coal mining operation in Latin America, with an estimated 28.4 million tons mined in 2006.<ref name=TFTS06/><ref name=M-T>{{cite web |url=http://www.mining-technology.com/projects/cerrejon/ |title=El Cerrej\u00f3n Coal Mine, Colombia |work=Mining-technology.com |publisher=Net Resources International |accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n{{clearboth}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite LSA |last=Hastings |first=Alexander K. |last2=Bloch |first2=Jonathan I. |last3=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first3=Carlos A. |year=2011 |title=A new longirostrine Dyrosaurid (Crocodylomorpha, Mesoeucrocodylia) from the Paleocene of north-eastern Colombia: Biogeographocal and behavioural implications for New-World Dyrosayridae |url=http://www.stri.si.edu/sites/publications/PDFs/STRI-W_Jaramillo_2011_Hasting_croc_Cerrejon.pdf |journal=[[Palaeontology (journal)|Palaeontology]] |volume=54 |pages=1095\u20131116 |accessdate=2017-06-14}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Head |first=J.J. |last2=Bloch |first2=J.I. |last3=Hastings |first3=A.K. |last4=Bourque |first4=J.R. |last5=[[Edwin Cadena|Cadena]] |first5=E.A. |last6=Herrera |first6=F.A. |last7=Polly |first7=P.D. |last8=[[Carlos Jaramillo (geologist)|Jaramillo]] |first8=C.A. |year=2009 |title=Giant boid snake from the paleocene neotropics reveals hotter past equatorial temperatures |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v457/n7230/abs/nature07671.html |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=457 |pages=715\u2013718 |accessdate=2017-06-14|bibcode=2009Natur.457..715H |doi=10.1038/nature07671 }}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Ojeda Marulanda |first=Carolina |last2=S\u00e1nchez Qui\u00f1\u00f3nez |first2=Carlos Alberto |year=2013 |title=Petrograf\u00eda, petrolog\u00eda y an\u00e1lisis de procedencia de unidades pale\u00f3genas en las cuencas Cesar - Rancher\u00eda y Catatumbo |